# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-solidarity-party
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 8, 2016.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican ticket of businessman Donald Trump and Indiana governor Mike Pence defeated the Democratic ticket of former secretary of state Hillary Clinton and Virginia junior senator Tim Kaine, in what was considered one of the biggest political upsets in American history.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was the fifth and most recent presidential election in which the winning candidate lost the popular vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Democratic president Barack Obama was ineligible to pursue a third term due to the term limits established by the Twenty-second Amendment to the U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton—wife of former president Bill Clinton and as such a former first lady—secured the nomination over U.S. senator Bernie Sanders in the Democratic primary and became the first female presidential nominee of a major American political party.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Initially considered a novelty candidate, Trump presented himself as a blunt-spoken political outsider and emerged as the Republican front-runner, defeating several notable opponents, including U.S. senators Ted Cruz and Marco Rubio, as well as governors John Kasich and Jeb Bush.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump's right-wing populist and nationalist campaign promised to "Make America Great Again" and opposed political correctness and many US free trade agreements, while supporting a more hard-line approach on illegal immigration.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump garnered extensive free media coverage due to his inflammatory comments.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton emphasized her extensive political experience; denounced Trump and half of his supporters as "deplorable" bigots and extremists; and advocated the expansion of Obama's policies, stressing racial equality, LGBT rights, women's rights, and inclusive capitalism.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The tone of the election campaign was widely characterized as divisive, negative, and troubling.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump faced controversy over his views on race and immigration, incidents of violence against protesters at his rallies, and numerous sexual misconduct allegations including the *Access Hollywood* tape.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton led in almost every nationwide and swing-state poll, with some predictive models giving her over a 90 percent chance of victory.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On election day, Trump over-performed his polls, winning several key swing states to achieve a majority in the Electoral College while losing the nationwide popular vote by 2.87 million votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Key to Trump's pivotal upset victory were his wins in the Democratic-leaning Rust Belt states of Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin, which he carried by fewer than 80,000 votes in the three "blue wall" states combined and gained a combined 46 electoral votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump's surprise victories were perceived to have been assisted by Clinton's lack of campaigning in some swing states (especially Wisconsin), the rightward shift of the white working class, as well as the influence of Obama–Trump voters and Sanders–Trump voters.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ultimately, Trump received 304 electoral votes to Clinton's 227, as two faithless electors defected from Trump and five from Clinton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump was the first president with neither prior public service nor military experience.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With ballot access to the entire national electorate, Libertarian nominee Gary Johnson received nearly 4.5 million votes (3.27%), the highest nationwide vote share for a third-party candidate since Ross Perot in 1996, while Green Party nominee Jill Stein received almost 1.45 million votes (1.06%).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Independent candidate Evan McMullin received 21.4% of the vote in his home state of Utah, the highest share of the vote for a non-major party candidate in any state since 1992.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Intelligence Community concluded that the Russian government had interfered in the election in order to "undermine public faith in the U.S. democratic process, denigrate Secretary Clinton, and harm her electability and potential presidency".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A Special Counsel investigation concluded in March 2019 that Russia had interfered "in sweeping and systematic fashion" in favor of Trump's candidacy but did not establish that members of the Trump campaign colluded with the Russian government.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] President Barack Obama, a Democrat and former U.S. senator from Illinois, was ineligible to seek reelection to a third term due to the restrictions of the American presidential term limits established by the Twenty-second Amendment.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both the Democratic and Republican parties, as well as third parties such as the Green and Libertarian parties, held a series of presidential primary elections and caucuses that took place between February and June 2016, staggered among the 50 states, the District of Columbia, and U.S. territories.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This nominating process was also an indirect election, where voters cast ballots for a slate of delegates to a political party's nominating convention, who in turn elected their party's presidential nominee.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Speculation about the 2016 campaign began almost immediately following the 2012 campaign, with *New York* magazine declaring that the race had begun in an article published on November 8, two days after the 2012 election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the same day, *Politico* released an article predicting that the 2016 general election would be between Clinton and former Florida Governor Jeb Bush, while an article in *The New York Times* named New Jersey Governor Chris Christie and Senator Cory Booker from New Jersey as potential candidates.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With seventeen major candidates entering the race, starting with Ted Cruz on March 23, 2015, this was the largest presidential primary field for any political party in American history, before being overtaken by the 2020 Democratic presidential primaries.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Prior to the Iowa caucuses on February 1, 2016, Perry, Walker, Jindal, Graham, and Pataki withdrew due to low polling numbers.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite leading many polls in Iowa, Trump came in second to Cruz, after which Huckabee, Paul, and Santorum withdrew due to poor performances at the ballot box.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Following a sizable victory for Trump in the New Hampshire primary, Christie, Fiorina, and Gilmore abandoned the race.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush followed suit after scoring fourth place to Trump, Rubio, and Cruz in South Carolina.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 1, the first of four "Super Tuesday" primaries, Rubio won his first contest in Minnesota, Cruz won Alaska, Oklahoma, and his home state of Texas, and Trump won the other seven states that voted.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Failing to gain traction, Carson suspended his campaign a few days later.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 15, the second "Super Tuesday", Kasich won his only contest in his home state of Ohio, and Trump won five primaries including Florida.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Rubio suspended his campaign after losing his home state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Between March 16 and May 3, only three candidates remained in the race: Trump, Cruz, and Kasich.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Cruz won the most delegates in four Western contests and in Wisconsin, keeping a credible path to denying Trump the nomination on the first ballot with 1,237 delegates.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump then augmented his lead by scoring landslide victories in his home state of New York and five Northeastern states in April, followed by a decisive victory in Indiana on May 3, securing all 57 of the state's delegates.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Without any further chances of forcing a contested convention, both Cruz and Kasich suspended their campaigns.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump remained the only active candidate and was declared the presumptive Republican nominee by Republican National Committee chairman Reince Priebus on the evening of May 3.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A 2018 study found that media coverage of Trump led to increased public support for him during the primaries.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The study showed that Trump received nearly $2 billion in free media, more than double any other candidate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Sides argued that Trump's polling surge was "almost certainly" due to frequent media coverage of his campaign.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Sides concluded "Trump is surging in the polls because the news media has consistently focused on him since he announced his candidacy on June 16".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Prior to clinching the Republican nomination, Trump received little support from establishment Republicans.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Major candidates were determined by the various media based on common consensus.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The following were invited to sanctioned televised debates based on their poll ratings.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump received 14,010,177 total votes in the primary.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump, Cruz, Rubio and Kasich each won at least one primary, with Trump receiving the highest number of votes and Ted Cruz receiving the second highest.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump turned his attention towards selecting a running mate after he became the presumptive nominee on May 4.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In mid-June, Eli Stokols and Burgess Everett of *Politico* reported that the Trump campaign was considering New Jersey Governor Chris Christie, former Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich from Georgia, Senator Jeff Sessions of Alabama, and Oklahoma Governor Mary Fallin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A June 30 report from *The Washington Post* also included Senators Bob Corker from Tennessee, Richard Burr from North Carolina, Tom Cotton from Arkansas, Joni Ernst from Iowa, and Indiana governor Mike Pence as individuals still being considered for the ticket.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump also said he was considering two military generals for the position, including retired Lieutenant General Michael Flynn.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was on July 12 reported that Trump had narrowed his list of possible running mates down to three: Christie, Gingrich, and Pence.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Two days later, several major media outlets reported that Trump had selected Pence as his running mate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump confirmed these reports in a Twittermessage on July 15, and formally made the announcement the following day in New York.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 19, the second night of the 2016 Republican National Convention, Pence won the Republican vice presidential nomination by acclamation.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Former secretary of state Hillary Clinton, who also served in the U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senate and was the first lady of the United States, became the first Democrat in the field to formally launch a major candidacy for the presidency with an announcement on April 12, 2015, via a video message.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] September 2015 polling numbers indicated a narrowing gap between Clinton and Sanders.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On October 20, Webb announced his withdrawal from the primaries, and explored a potential independent run.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The next day, Vice President Joe Biden decided not to run, ending months of speculation, stating, "While I will not be a candidate, I will not be silent".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On October 23, Chafee withdrew, stating that he hoped for "an end to the endless wars and the beginning of a new era for the United States and humanity".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On November 2, after failing to qualify for the second DNC-sanctioned debate after adoption of a rule change negated polls which before might have necessitated his inclusion in the debate, Lessig withdrew as well, narrowing the field to Clinton, O'Malley, and Sanders.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On February 1, 2016, Clinton won the Iowa caucuses by a margin of 0.2 points over Sanders.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After winning no delegates in Iowa, O'Malley withdrew from the presidential race that day.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On February 9, Sanders bounced back to win the New Hampshire primary with 60% of the vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the remaining two February contests, Clinton won the Nevada caucuses with 53% of the vote and scored a decisive victory in the South Carolina primary with 73% of the vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 1, eleven states participated in the first of four "Super Tuesday" primaries.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton won Alabama, Arkansas, Georgia, Massachusetts, Tennessee, Texas, and Virginia and 504 pledged delegates, while Sanders won Colorado, Minnesota, Oklahoma, and his home state of Vermont and 340 delegates.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The following weekend, Sanders won victories in Kansas, Nebraska, and Maine with 15- to 30-point margins, while Clinton won the Louisiana primary with 71% of the vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 8, despite never having a lead in the Michigan primary, Sanders won by a small margin of 1.5 points and outperforming polls by over 19 points, while Clinton won 83% of the vote in Mississippi.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 15, the second "Super Tuesday", Clinton won in Florida, Illinois, Missouri, North Carolina, and Ohio.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Between March 22 and April 9, Sanders won six caucuses in Idaho, Utah, Alaska, Hawaii, Washington, and Wyoming, as well as the Wisconsin primary, while Clinton won the Arizona primary.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On April 19, Clinton won the New York primary with 58% of the vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On April 26, in the third "Super Tuesday" dubbed the "Acela primary", she won contests in Connecticut, Delaware, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, while Sanders won in Rhode Island.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Over the course of May, Sanders accomplished another surprise win in the Indiana primary and also won in West Virginia and Oregon, while Clinton won the Guam caucus and Kentucky primary (and also non-binding primaries in Nebraska and Washington).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On June 4–5, Clinton won two victories in the Virgin Islands caucus and Puerto Rico primary.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On June 7, Clinton secured a majority of pledged delegates after winning primaries in California, New Jersey, New Mexico, and South Dakota, while Sanders won only Montana and North Dakota.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton also won the final primary in the District of Columbia on June 14.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the conclusion of the primary process, Clinton had won 2,204 pledged delegates (54% of the total) awarded by the primary elections and caucuses, while Sanders had won 1,847 (46%).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Out of the 714 unpledged delegates or "superdelegates" who were set to vote in the convention in July, Clinton received endorsements from 560 (78%), while Sanders received 47 (7%).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Sanders had not formally dropped out of the race, he announced on June 16, that his main goal in the coming months would be to work with Clinton to defeat Trump in the general election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 8, appointees from the Clinton campaign, the Sanders campaign, and the Democratic National Committee negotiated a draft of the party's platform.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 12, Sanders formally endorsed Clinton at a rally in New Hampshire in which he appeared with her.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Sanders then went on to headline 39 campaign rallies on behalf of Clinton in 13 key states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The following candidates were frequently interviewed by major broadcast networks and cable news channels or were listed in publicly published national polls.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lessig was invited to one forum, but withdrew when rules were changed which prevented him from participating in officially sanctioned debates.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton received 16,849,779 votes in the primary.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In April 2016, the Clinton campaign began to compile a list of 15 to 20 individuals to vet for the position of running mate, even though Sanders continued to challenge Clinton in the Democratic primaries.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Subsequent reports stated that Clinton was also considering Secretary of Agriculture Tom Vilsack, retired Admiral James Stavridis, and Governor John Hickenlooper of Colorado.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In discussing her potential vice presidential choice, Clinton said the most important attribute she looked for was the ability and experience to immediately step into the role of president.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 22, Clinton announced that she had chosen Senator Tim Kaine from Virginia as her running mate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The delegates at the 2016 Democratic National Convention, which took place July 25–28, formally nominated the Democratic ticket.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Third party and independent candidates who obtained more than 100,000 votes nationally or on ballot in at least 15 states are listed separately.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In some states, Evan McMullin's running mate was listed as Nathan Johnson on the ballot rather than Mindy Finn, although Nathan Johnson was intended to only be a placeholder until an actual running mate was chosen.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hillary Clinton focused her candidacy on several themes, including raising middle class incomes, expanding women's rights, instituting campaign finance reform, and improving the Affordable Care Act.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Donald Trump's campaign drew heavily on his personal image, enhanced by his previous media exposure.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The primary slogan of the Trump campaign, extensively used on campaign merchandise, was Make America Great Again.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The red baseball cap with the slogan emblazoned on the front became a symbol of the campaign and has been frequently donned by Trump and his supporters.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump's right-wing populist positions—reported by *The New Yorker* to be nativist, protectionist, and semi-isolationist—differ in many ways from traditional U.S. conservatism.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He opposed many free trade deals and military interventionist policies that conservatives generally support, and opposed cuts in Medicare and Social Security benefits.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Moreover, he has insisted that Washington is "broken" and can be fixed only by an outsider.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Support for Trump was high among working and middle-class white male voters with annual incomes of less than $50,000 and no college degree.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This group, particularly those without a high-school diploma, suffered a decline in their income in recent years.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to *The Washington Post*, support for Trump is higher in areas with a higher mortality rate for middle-aged white people.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A sample of interviews with more than 11,000 Republican-leaning respondents from August to December 2015 found that Trump at that time found his strongest support among Republicans in West Virginia, followed by New York, and then followed by six Southern states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton had an uneasy—and, at times, adversarial—relationship with the press throughout her life in public service.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Weeks before her official entry as a presidential candidate, Clinton attended a political press corps event, pledging to start fresh on what she described as a "complicated" relationship with political reporters.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton was initially criticized by the press for avoiding taking their questions, after which she provided more interviews.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In contrast, Trump benefited from free media more than any other candidate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] From the beginning of his campaign through February 2016, Trump received almost $2 billion in free media attention, twice the amount that Clinton received.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to data from the *Tyndall Report*, which tracks nightly news content, through February 2016, Trump alone accounted for more than a quarter of all 2016 election coverage on the evening newscasts of NBC, CBS and ABC, more than all the Democratic campaigns combined.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Observers noted Trump's ability to garner constant mainstream media coverage "almost at will".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Trump frequently criticized the media for writing what he alleged to be false stories about him and he has called upon his supporters to be "the silent majority".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump also said the media "put false meaning into the words I say", and says he does not mind being criticized by the media as long as they are honest about it.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to a wide range of representative polls, both Clinton and Trump had significant net-unfavorability ratings, and their controversial reputations set the tone of the campaign.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton's practice during her time as Secretary of State of using a private email address and server, in lieu of State Department servers, gained widespread public attention back in March 2015.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Concerns were raised about security and preservation of emails, and the possibility that laws may have been violated.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After allegations were raised that some of the emails in question fell into this so-called "born classified" category, an FBI probe was initiated regarding how classified information was handled on the Clinton server.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The FBI probe was concluded on July 5, 2016, with a recommendation of no charges, a recommendation that was followed by the Justice Department.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Also, on September 9, Clinton said: "You know, just to be grossly generalistic, you could put half of Trump's supporters into what I call the basket of deplorables.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Donald Trump criticized her remark as insulting his supporters.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The following day Clinton expressed regret for saying "half", while insisting that Trump had deplorably amplified "hateful views and voices".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Previously on August 25, Clinton gave a speech criticizing Trump's campaign for using "racist lies" and allowing the alt-right to gain prominence.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On September 11, Clinton left a 9/11 memorial event early due to illness.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Video footage of Clinton's departure showed Clinton becoming unsteady on her feet and being helped into a van.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Later that evening, Clinton reassured reporters that she was "feeling great".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After initially stating that Clinton had become overheated at the event, her campaign later added that she had been diagnosed with pneumonia two days earlier.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The media criticized the Clinton campaign for a lack of transparency regarding Clinton's illness.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton cancelled a planned trip to California due to her illness.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The episode drew renewed public attention to questions about Clinton's health.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the other side, on October 7, video and accompanying audio were released by *The Washington Post* in which Trump referred obscenely to women in a 2005 conversation with Billy Bush while they were preparing to film an episode of *Access Hollywood*.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the recording, Trump described his attempts to initiate a sexual relationship with a married woman and added that women would allow male celebrities to grope their genitalia (Trump used the phrase "grab 'em by the pussy").
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The audio was met with a reaction of disbelief and disgust from the media.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Following the revelation, Trump's campaign issued an apology, stating that the video was of a private conversation from "many years ago".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The incident was condemned by numerous prominent Republicans like Reince Priebus, Mitt Romney, John Kasich, Jeb Bush and the Speaker of the House Paul Ryan.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Many believed the video had doomed Trump's chances for election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] By October 8, several dozen Republicans had called for Trump to withdraw from the campaign and let Pence and Condoleezza Rice head the ticket.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump insisted he would never drop out, but apologized for his remarks.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump also delivered strong and controversial statements towards Muslims and Islam on the campaign trail, saying, "I think Islam hates us".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was criticized and also supported for his statement at a rally declaring, "Donald J.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump is calling for a total and complete shutdown of Muslims entering the United States until our country's representatives can figure out what is going on".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Additionally, Trump announced that he would "look into" surveilling mosques, and mentioned potentially going after the families of domestic terrorists in the wake of the San Bernardino shooting.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His strong rhetoric towards Muslims resulted in leadership from both parties condemning his statements.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, many of his supporters shared their support for his proposed travel ban, despite the backlash.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Throughout the campaign, Trump indicated in interviews, speeches, and Twitter posts that he would refuse to recognize the outcome of the election if he was defeated.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump falsely stated that the election would be rigged against him.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the final presidential debate of 2016, Trump refused to tell Fox News anchor Chris Wallace whether or not he would accept the election results.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The rejection of election results by a major nominee would have been unprecedented at the time as no major presidential candidate had ever refused to accept the outcome of an election until Trump did so himself in the following 2020 presidential election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The ongoing controversy of the election made third parties attract voters' attention.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 3, 2016, Libertarian Gary Johnson addressed the Conservative Political Action Conference in Washington, DC, touting himself as the third-party option for anti-Trump Republicans.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In early May, some commentators opined that Johnson was moderate enough to pull votes away from both Hillary Clinton and Donald Trump who were very disliked and polarizing.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson also began to get time on national television, being invited on ABC News, NBC News, CBS News, CNN, Fox News, MSNBC, Bloomberg, and many other networks.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In September–October 2016, Johnson suffered a "string of damaging stumbles when he has fielded questions about foreign affairs".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On September 8, Johnson, when he appeared on MSNBC's *Morning Joe*, was asked by panelist Mike Barnicle, "What would you do, if you were elected, about Aleppo?" (referring to a war-torn city in Syria).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson responded, "And what is Aleppo?" His response prompted widespread attention, much of it negative.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Later that day, Johnson said that he had "blanked" and that he did "understand the dynamics of the Syrian conflict—I talk about them every day".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the other hand, Green Party candidate Jill Stein said the Democratic and Republican parties are "two corporate parties" that have converged into one.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Concerned by the rise of the far right internationally and the tendency towards neoliberalism within the Democratic Party, she has said, "The answer to neofascism is stopping neoliberalism.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Putting another Clinton in the White House will fan the flames of this right-wing extremism".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On October 28, eleven days before the election, FBI Director James Comey informed Congress that the FBI was analyzing additional Clinton emails obtained during its investigation of an unrelated case.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On November 6, he notified Congress that the new emails did not change the FBI's earlier conclusion.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the week following the "Comey Letter" of October 28, Clinton's lead dropped by 3 percentage points, leading some commentators - including Clinton herself - to conclude that this letter cost her the election, though there are dissenting views.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wall Street spent a record $2 billion trying to influence the 2016 United States presidential election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The following table is an overview of the money used in the campaign as it was reported to Federal Election Commission (FEC) and released in September 2016.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Outside groups are independent expenditure-only committees – also called PACs and SuperPACs.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The sources of the numbers are the FEC and OpenSecrets.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some spending totals are not available, due to withdrawals before the FEC deadline.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As of September 2016, ten candidates with ballot access had filed financial reports with the FEC.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 2016 presidential election was the first in 50 years without all the protections of the original Voting Rights Act of 1965.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Fourteen states had new voting restrictions in place, including swing states such as Virginia and Wisconsin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Among states that offered early in-person voting to all voters in 2016, 27 percent of all votes were cast early in person.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Across states where mail voting was available to all voters, 34 percent of all votes were cast by mail.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nationwide, a total of 40 percent of votes were cast before Election Day in the 2016 general election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton was endorsed by *The New York Times*, the *Los Angeles Times*, the *Houston Chronicle*, the *San Jose Mercury News*, the *Chicago Sun-Times* and the *New York Daily News* editorial boards.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Several papers which endorsed Clinton, such as the *Houston Chronicle*, *The Dallas Morning News*, *The San Diego Union-Tribune*, *The Columbus Dispatch* and *The Arizona Republic*, endorsed their first Democratic candidate for many decades.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] *The Atlantic*, which has been in circulation since 1857, gave Clinton its third-ever endorsement (after Abraham Lincoln and Lyndon Johnson).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump, who frequently criticized the mainstream media, was not endorsed by the vast majority of newspapers.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The *Las Vegas Review-Journal*, *The Florida Times-Union*, and the tabloid *National Enquirer* were his highest profile supporters.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] *USA Today*, which had not endorsed any candidate since it was founded in 1982, broke tradition by giving an anti-endorsement against Trump, declaring him "unfit for the presidency".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gary Johnson received endorsements from several major daily newspapers, including the *Chicago Tribune*, and the *Richmond Times-Dispatch*.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Other traditionally Republican papers, including the *New Hampshire Union Leader*, which had endorsed the Republican nominee in every election for the last 100 years, and *The Detroit News*, which had not endorsed a non-Republican in its 143 years, endorsed Gary Johnson.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Commission on Presidential Debates (CPD), a non-profit organization, hosted debates between qualifying presidential and vice-presidential candidates.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The three locations (Hofstra University, Washington University in St.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Louis, University of Nevada, Las Vegas) chosen to host the presidential debates, and the one location (Longwood University) selected to host the vice presidential debate, were announced in September 2015.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The site of the first debate was originally designated as Wright State University in Dayton, Ohio; however, due to rising costs and security concerns, the debate was moved to Hofstra University in Hempstead, New York.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On August 19, Kellyanne Conway, Trump's campaign manager confirmed that Trump would participate in a series of three debates.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] There were also debates between independent candidates.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The news media and election experts were surprised at Trump's winning of the Electoral College.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On the eve of the vote, spread betting firm Spreadex had Clinton at an Electoral College spread of 307–322 against Trump's 216–231.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The final polls showed a lead by Clinton, and in the end she did receive more votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump himself expected, based on polling, to lose the election, and rented a small hotel ballroom to make a brief concession speech, later remarking: "I said if we're going to lose I don't want a big ballroom".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump performed surprisingly well in all battleground states, especially Florida, Iowa, Ohio, and North Carolina.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Even the Democratic-leaning Rust Belt states of Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin were narrowly won by Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] According to the authors of *Shattered: Inside Hillary Clinton's Doomed Campaign*, the White House had concluded by late Tuesday night that Trump would win the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama's political director David Simas called Clinton campaign manager Robby Mook to persuade Clinton to concede the election, with no success.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama then called Clinton directly, citing the importance of continuity of government, to ask her to publicly acknowledge that Trump had won.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Believing that Clinton was still unwilling to concede, the president then called her campaign chair John Podesta, but the call to Clinton had likely already persuaded her.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Associated Press called Pennsylvania for Trump at 1:35 AM EST, putting Trump at 267 electoral votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] By 2:01 AM EST, they had called both Maine and Nebraska's second congressional districts for Trump, putting him at 269 electoral votes, making it impossible for Clinton to reach 270.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] One minute after this, John Podesta told Hillary Clinton's victory party in New York that the election was too close to call.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At 2:29 AM EST, the Associated Press called Wisconsin, and the election, for Trump, giving him 279 electoral votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] By 2:37 AM EST, Clinton had called Trump to concede the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On Wednesday morning at 2:30 AM EST, it was reported that Trump had secured Wisconsin's 10 electoral votes, giving him a majority of the 538 electors in the Electoral College, enough to make him the president-elect of the United States, and Trump gave his victory speech at 2:50 AM EST.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Later that day, Clinton asked her supporters to accept the result and hoped that Trump would be "a successful president for all Americans".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In his speech, Trump appealed for unity, saying "it is time for us to come together as one united people", and praised Clinton as someone who was owed "a major debt of gratitude for her service to our country".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump won the 2016 election with 56.9% of the electoral college—placing the win in approximately the 23rd percentile of all presidential elections.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's 2016 victory was among the few in which the electoral college winner received fewer popular votes than the rival (right end of chart).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The 2016 election was the fifth and most recent presidential election in which the winning candidate lost the popular vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Six states plus a portion of Maine that Obama won in 2012 switched to Trump (Electoral College votes in parentheses): Florida (29), Pennsylvania (20), Ohio (18), Michigan (16), Wisconsin (10), Iowa (6), and Maine's second congressional district (1).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Initially, Trump won exactly 100 more Electoral College votes than Mitt Romney had in 2012, with two lost to faithless electors in the final tally.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Thirty-nine states swung more Republican compared to the previous presidential election, while eleven states and the District of Columbia swung more Democratic.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Based on United States Census Bureau estimates of the voting age population (VAP), turnout of voters casting a vote for president was nearly 1% higher than in 2012.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Examining overall turnout in the 2016 election, the University of Florida's Michael McDonald estimated that 138.8 million Americans cast a ballot.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Considering a VAP of 250.6 million people and a voting-eligible population (VEP) of 230.6 million people, this is a turnout rate of 55.4% VAP and 60.2% VEP.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Based on this estimate, voter turnout was up compared to 2012 (54.1% VAP) but down compared to 2008 (57.4% VAP).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] An FEC report of the election recorded an official total of 136.7 million votes cast for president—more than any prior election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] By losing New York, Trump became the fourth and most recent victorious candidate to lose his home state, which also occurred in 1844, 1916, and 1968.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Furthermore, along with James Polk in 1844, Trump is one of two victorious presidential nominees to win without either their home state or birth state (in this case, both were New York).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Data scientist Hamdan Azhar noted the paradoxes of the 2016 outcome, saying that "chief among them [was] the discrepancy between the popular vote, which Hillary Clinton won by 2.8 million votes, and the electoral college, where Trump won 304–227".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He said Trump outperformed Mitt Romney's 2012 results, while Clinton only just matched Barack Obama's 2012 totals.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Hamdan also said Trump was "the highest vote earner of any Republican candidate ever", exceeding George W.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush's 62.04 million votes in 2004, though neither reached Clinton's 65.9 million, nor Obama's 69.5 million votes in 2008.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He concluded, with help from *The Cook Political Report*, that the election hinged not on Clinton's large 2.8 million overall vote margin over Trump, but rather on about 78,000 votes from only three counties in Wisconsin, Pennsylvania, and Michigan.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton was the first former Secretary of State to be nominated by a major political party since James G.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the first election since 1988 in which the Republican nominee won the states of Michigan and Pennsylvania, and the first since 1984 in which they won Wisconsin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was the first time since 1988 that the Republican nominee won Maine's second congressional district and the first time since George W.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush's victory in New Hampshire in 2000 that they won any electoral votes in the Northeast.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton only narrowly won New Hampshire by 0.37% (2,736 votes).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This marked the first time that Maine split its electoral votes since it began awarding them based on congressional districts in 1972, and the first time the state split its electoral vote since 1828.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was also the sixth presidential election in which both major party candidates were registered in the same home state; the others have been in 1860, 1904, 1920, 1940, and 1944.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was also the first election since 1928 that the Republicans won without having either Richard Nixon or one of the Bushes on the ticket.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This election was the first since 1908 where neither candidate was currently serving in public office.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the first election since 1980 where a Republican was elected without carrying every former Confederate state in the process, as Trump lost Virginia in this election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was also the first presidential election since 1876 in which Virginia voted Democratic while Florida voted Republican, which has occurred in every subsequent presidential election as well.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Although both Virginia and Florida voted for Republican George W.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush and Democrat Barack Obama twice, Virginia became a blue state while Florida became a red state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Florida backed Trump even when he lost the electoral vote in 2020, and Virginia backed Kamala Harris even though she lost the popular vote in 2024.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump became the first Republican to earn more than 300 electoral votes since the 1988 election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the first time since 1976 that a Republican presidential candidate lost a pledged vote via a faithless elector, and, additionally, this was the first time since 1972 that the winning presidential candidate lost an electoral vote due to faithless electors.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Johnson received the highest ever share of the vote for a Libertarian nominee, surpassing Ed Clark's 1980 result.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Independent candidate Evan McMullin, who appeared on the ballot in eleven states, received over 732,000 votes (0.53%).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He won 21.4% of the vote in his home state of Utah, the highest share of the vote for a third-party candidate in any state since 1992.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Despite dropping out of the election following his defeat in the Democratic primary, Senator Bernie Sanders received 5.7% of the vote in his home state of Vermont, the highest write-in draft campaign percentage for a presidential candidate in American history.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Johnson and McMullin were the first third-party candidates since Nader to receive at least 5% of the vote in one or more states, with Johnson crossing the mark in nine states and McMullin crossing it in two.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At age 70, Trump was the oldest non-incumbent ever to win a presidential election, surpassing Ronald Reagan's record in 1980, who was first elected at age 69.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Four years later, in 2020, Biden surpassed this record at age 77, as did Trump again in 2024 at age 78.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Of the 3,153 counties/districts/independent cities making returns, Trump won the most popular votes in 2,649 (84.02%) while Clinton carried 504 (15.98%).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 1980, Democrat Jimmy Carter carried his home state of Georgia, despite losing the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Pence received 305 electoral votes for vice president, but only 304 as part of the Trump–Pence ticket; one faithless elector from Texas voted for Ron Paul as president instead of Trump, and is recorded separately below.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The exact numbers of write-in votes have been published for three states: California, New Hampshire, and Vermont.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Two faithless electors from Texas cast their presidential votes for Ron Paul and John Kasich, respectively.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Chris Suprun said he cast his presidential vote for John Kasich and his vice presidential vote for Carly Fiorina.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The other faithless elector in Texas, Bill Greene, cast his presidential vote for Ron Paul but cast his vice presidential vote for Mike Pence, as pledged.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] John Kasich received recorded write-in votes in Alabama, Georgia, Illinois, New Hampshire, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, and Vermont.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The table below displays the official vote tallies by each state's Electoral College voting method.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The source for the results of all states is the official Federal Election Commission report.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The column labeled "Margin" shows Trump's margin of victory over Clinton (the margin is negative for every state that Clinton won).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A total of 29 third party and independent presidential candidates appeared on the ballot in at least one state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Former Governor of New Mexico Gary Johnson and physician Jill Stein repeated their 2012 roles as the nominees for the Libertarian Party and the Green Party, respectively.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Aside from Florida and North Carolina, the states that secured Trump's victory are situated in the Great Lakes/Rust Belt region.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Wisconsin went Republican for the first time since 1984, while Pennsylvania and Michigan went Republican for the first time since 1988.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Stein petitioned for a recount in Wisconsin, Michigan, and Pennsylvania.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Clinton campaign pledged to participate in the Green Party recount efforts, while Trump backers challenged them in court.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Meanwhile, American Delta Party/Reform Party presidential candidate Rocky De La Fuente petitioned for and was granted a partial recount in Nevada.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] According to a 2021 study in *Science Advances*, conversion of voters who voted for Obama in 2012 to Trump in 2016 contributed to Republican flips in Ohio, Michigan, and Pennsylvania.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Two states (Maine and Nebraska) allow for their electoral votes to be split between candidates by congressional districts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The winner within each congressional district gets one electoral vote for the district.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The winner of the statewide vote gets two additional electoral votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Most media outlets announced the beginning of the presidential race about twenty months prior to Election Day.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Soon after the first contestants declared their candidacy, Larry Sabato listed Virginia, Colorado, Iowa, New Hampshire, Florida, Nevada, and Ohio as the seven states most likely to be contested in the general election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After Donald Trump clinched the Republican presidential nomination, many pundits felt that the major campaign locations might be different from what had originally been expected.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Rust Belt states such as Pennsylvania, Wisconsin, and even Michigan were thought to be in play with Trump as the nominee, while states with large minority populations, such as Colorado and Virginia, were expected to shift towards Clinton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] By the conventions period and the debates, however, it did not seem as though the Rust Belt states could deliver a victory to Trump, as many of them were considered to be part of the "blue wall" of Democratic-leaning states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's courting of the Polish-American vote, a sizable number of whom were Reagan Democrats, has been cited as the cause for the loss of the Rust Belt by the Democratic nominee.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] According to Politico and FiveThirtyEight, his path to victory went through states such as Florida, North Carolina, Nevada, New Hampshire, and possibly Colorado.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Early polling indicated a closer-than-usual race in former Democratic strongholds such as Washington, Delaware, New Jersey, Connecticut, Maine (for the two statewide electoral votes), and New Mexico.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A consensus among political pundits developed throughout the primary election season regarding swing states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] From the results of presidential elections from 2004 through to 2012, the Democratic and Republican parties would generally start with a safe electoral vote count of about 150 to 200.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, the margins required to constitute a swing state are vague, and can vary between groups of analysts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was thought that left-leaning states in the Rust Belt could become more conservative, as Trump had strong appeal among many blue-collar workers.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They represent a large portion of the American populace and were a major factor in Trump's eventual nomination.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's primary campaign was propelled by victories in Democratic states, and his supporters often did not identify as Republican.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Media reports indicated that both candidates planned to concentrate on Florida, Pennsylvania, Ohio and North Carolina.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Among the Republican-leaning states, potential Democratic targets included Nebraska's second congressional district, Georgia, and Arizona.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's relatively poor polling in some traditionally Republican states, such as Utah, raised the possibility that they could vote for Clinton, despite easy wins there by recent Republican nominees.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, many analysts asserted that these states were not yet viable Democratic destinations.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Several sites and individuals publish electoral predictions.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] These generally rate the race by the likelihood for each party to win a state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The "tossup" label is usually used to indicate that neither party has an advantage, "lean" to indicate a party has a slight edge, "likely" to indicate a party has a clear but not overwhelming advantage, and "safe" to indicate a party has an advantage that cannot be overcome.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As the parameters of the race established themselves, analysts converged on a narrower list of contested states, which were relatively similar to those of recent elections.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On November 7, the Cook Political Report categorized Arizona, Colorado, Florida, Iowa, Michigan, Nevada, New Hampshire, North Carolina, Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin as states with close races.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Additionally, a district from each of Maine and Nebraska were considered to be coin flips.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nate Silver, the publication's editor-in-chief, subsequently removed Texas, South Carolina, Missouri, and Indiana from the list after the race tightened significantly.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] These conclusions were supported by models such as the Princeton Elections Consortium, the New York Times Upshot, and punditry evaluations from Sabato's Crystal Ball and the Cook Political Report.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Hillary Clinton won states like New Mexico by less than 10 percentage points.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Among the states where the candidates finished at a margin of within seven percent, Clinton won Virginia (13 electoral votes), Colorado (9), Maine (2), Minnesota (10), and New Hampshire (4).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On the other hand, Trump won Michigan (16), Pennsylvania (20), Wisconsin (10), Florida (29), North Carolina (15), Arizona (11), Nebraska's second district (1), and Georgia (16).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] States won by Obama in the 2012, such as Ohio (18), Iowa (6), and Maine's second district (1), were also won by Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The close result in Maine was not expected by most commentators, nor were Trump's victory of over 10 points in the second district and their disparities.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The dramatic shift of Midwestern states towards Trump were contrasted in the media against the relative movement of Southern states towards the Democrats.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] For example, former Democratic strongholds such as Minnesota and Maine leaned towards the GOP while still voting Democratic, albeit by smaller margins.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Meanwhile, Iowa voted more Republican than Texas did, Georgia was more Democratic than Ohio, and the margin of victory for Trump was greater in North Carolina than Arizona.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's smaller victories in Alaska and Utah also took some experts by surprise.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] North Dakota had the largest swing towards Trump in 2016, while Utah had the largest swing towards Clinton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Red denotes states or congressional districts won by Republican Donald Trump; blue denotes those won by Democrat Hillary Clinton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The 2016 election was highly viewed, setting viewership records on CNN and Fox News.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Over 28 million people watched the election on cable television, with 63.99 million viewers including broadcast television.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p02] While more highly viewed than 2012 (60.86 million viewers), it was less viewed than 2008 (71.5 million viewers).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Voter demographic data for 2016 were collected by Edison Research for the National Election Pool, a consortium of ABC News, CBS News, MSNBC, CNN, Fox News, and the Associated Press.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The voter survey is based on exit polls completed by 24,537 voters leaving 350 voting places throughout the United States on Election Day, in addition to 4,398 telephone interviews with early and absentee voters.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump's crucial victories in the Midwest were aided in large part by his strong margins among non-college whites—while Obama lost those voters by a margin of 10 points in 2012, Clinton lost this group by 20 percent.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The election also represented the first time that Republicans performed better among lower-income whites than among affluent white voters.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Clinton however had the majority amongst lower-income Americans overall.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Voters 40 years of age or older (born in 1976 or earlier) were estimated to comprise 64% of the electorate in the exit poll.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The Pew Research Center later showed that the Greatest Generation, the Silent Generation, Baby boomers, and Generation X accounted for 155 million of the 224 million eligible voters (or approximately 69%).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Baby boomers and Generation X alone comprised 127 million of the eligible voters (or approximately 57%).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] There was an age gap, with Clinton winning voters under the age of 40, while Trump won voters over the age of 40.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump narrowed Clinton's margin compared to Obama by seven points among blacks and African-Americans, eight points among Latinos, and 11 points among Asian-Americans.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Meanwhile, Trump increased his lead with non-Hispanic white voters through one percent over Mitt Romney's performance, and American Indians, Alaska Natives, and Pacific Islanders shifted their support towards the Republican candidate using the same relative amount.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Additionally, although 74 percent of Muslim voters supported Clinton, Trump nearly doubled his support among those voters compared to Mitt Romney at 13 percent, according to the *Council on American–Islamic Relations* exit poll.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] However, "more convincing data" from the polling firm Latino Decisions indicates that Clinton received a higher share of the Hispanic vote, and Trump a lower share, than the Edison exit polls showed.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Using wider, more geographically and linguistically representative sampling, Latino Decisions concluded that Clinton won 79% of Hispanic voters (also an improvement over Obama's share in 2008 and 2012), while Trump won only 18% (lower than previous Republicans such as Romney and McCain).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Additionally, the 2016 Cooperative Congressional Election Study found that Clinton's share of the Hispanic vote was one percentage point higher than Obama's in 2012, while Trump's was seven percentage points lower than Romney's.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Similarly, a large, multi-lingual study by the Asian American Legal Defense and Education Fund found that Clinton won 79% of Asian-American voters, higher than the Edison exit poll showed, while Trump won only 18%, a decrease from McCain's and Romney's numbers.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Furthermore, according to the AALDEF's report, Trump received merely 2% of the Muslim-American vote, whereas Clinton received 97%.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The low percentage of Muslim votes for Trump may have been influenced by much of his rhetoric during the campaign regarding Muslims and Islam.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The issue of islamophobia was demonstrated to be an important political issue for Muslim voters; an ISPU study done in 2016 found that, "...outside the issues of discrimination and Islamophobia there aren't, like, one or two big issues that unite all Muslims".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Various methods were used to forecast the outcome of the 2016 election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] There were many competing election forecast approaches including Nate Silver's FiveThirtyEight, The Upshot at *The New York Times*, *Daily Kos*, Princeton Election Consortium, Cook Political Report, Rothenberg and Gonzales, PollyVote, Sabato's Crystal Ball and Electoral-Vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] However, FiveThirtyEight's model pointed to the possibility of an Electoral College-popular vote split widening in the final weeks based on Trump's improvement in swing states like Florida or Pennsylvania.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Early exit polls generally favored Clinton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] After the polls closed and some of the results came in, the forecasts were found to be inaccurate, as Trump performed better in the competitive Midwestern states, such as Iowa, Ohio, and Minnesota, than expected.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Three Rust Belt states (Pennsylvania, Wisconsin and Michigan) which were considered to be part of Clinton's firewall, were narrowly won by Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Of the states in the Great Lakes region, Clinton won the swing state of Minnesota by one point, as well as traditional Democratic strongholds such as New York and Illinois with populous urban centers.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This result stands in contrast to that of 2012, when President Barack Obama won all but Indiana, which he narrowly carried in 2008.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This table displays the final polling average published by Real Clear Politics on November 7, the actual electoral margin, and the over-performance by either candidate relative to the polls.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Many pollsters were puzzled by the failure of mainstream forecasting models to predict the outcome of the 2016 election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Some journalists compared the 2016 election to the failure of prognosticator Arthur Henning in the "Dewey Defeats Truman" incident from the 1948 presidential election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Sean Trende, writing for *RealClearPolitics*, wrote that many of the polls were accurate, but that the pundits' interpretation of these polls neglected polling error.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Nate Silver found that the high number of undecided and third-party voters in the election was neglected in many of these models, and that many of these voters decided to vote for Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Political scientist Lloyd Gruber said, "One of the major casualties of the 2016 election season has been the reputation of political science, a discipline whose practitioners had largely dismissed Donald Trump's chances of gaining the Republican nomination".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump said that he was surprised, and added "I always used to believe in [polls].
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] FiveThirtyEight's final polls-plus forecast predicted 18 states, plus the second congressional districts of Maine and Nebraska, with an interval of confidence lower than 90%.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The lone exception was Maine's 2nd congressional district.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The following table displays the final winning probabilities given by each outlet, along with the final electoral result.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The states shown have been identified by Politico, WhipBoard, *The New York Times*, and the Crystal Ball as battlegrounds.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Elections analysts and political pundits issue probabilistic forecasts of the composition of the Electoral College.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] These forecasts use a variety of factors to estimate the likelihood of each candidate winning the Electoral College electors for that state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Below is a list of states considered by one or more forecasts to be competitive; states that are deemed to be "safe" or "solid" by forecasters *Sabato's Crystal Ball*, *New York Times*, *Princeton Election Consortium,* *PredictWise*, and *FiveThirtyEight*.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump's victory, considered unlikely by most forecasts, was characterized as an "upset" and as "shocking" by news organizations.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump himself thought he would lose even as the polls were closing.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Following the announcement of Trump's election, large protests broke out across the United States with some continuing for several days.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Protesters held up a number of different signs and chanted various shouts including "Not my president" and "We don't accept the president-elect".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The movement organized on Twitter under the hashtags #Antitrump and #NotMyPresident.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] High school and college students walked out of classes to protest.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] At a few protests fires were lit, flags and other items were burned and people yelled derogatory remarks about Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Rioters also broke glass at certain locations.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Celebrities such as Madonna, Cher, and Lady Gaga took part in New York.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Kendrick Lamar's song "Alright" was used repeatedly by protestors, despite the movement receiving no endorsement from Lamar himself.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Some protesters took to blocking freeways in Los Angeles, San Diego, and Portland, Oregon, and were dispersed by police in the early hours of the morning.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In a number of cities, protesters were dispersed with rubber bullets, pepper spray and bean-bags fired by police.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In New York City, calls were made to continue the protests over the coming days after the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Los Angeles mayor Eric Garcetti expressed understanding of the protests and praised those who peacefully wanted to make their voices heard.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] After the election, computer scientists, including J.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] However, statistician Nate Silver performed a regression analysis which demonstrated that the alleged discrepancy between paper ballots and electronic voting machines "completely disappears once you control for race and education level".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] On November 25, the Obama administration said the results from November 8 "accurately reflect the will of the American people".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The following day, the White House released another statement, saying: "the federal government did not observe any increased level of malicious cyberactivity aimed at disrupting our electoral process on Election Day".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] These states were run by Republicans so there was no way to find out the truth about any of them".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Donald Trump and New Hampshire governor Chris Sununu both complained that liberal voters from Massachusetts were illegally bused into New Hampshire for the 2016 election, and Scott Brown blamed the same phenomenon for losing his senate race in 2014.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The New Hampshire Secretary of State and New Hampshire Department of Justice issued a report in 2018 regarding complaints of voters being bused in from Vermont, Maine, and Massachusetts for the 2016 election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] They found that in every case, field inspectors were able to determine that the voters were from New Hampshire, though they were riding a bus operated by an out-of-state company (which has its name and address written on the outside of the bus, presumably the source of the confusion).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Out of 743,000 votes cast, four were determined to be cast illegally, either because the voters were told to go to the wrong location, or because the voter believed they were able to vote in each town in which they owned property.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Out of about 6,000 same-day voter registrations in the state, the report says only 66 voters could not have their residency confirmed (though fraud is not the only explanation for such a failure).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] On November 23, Green Party presidential candidate Jill Stein launched a public fundraiser to pay for recounts in Wisconsin, Michigan, and Pennsylvania, asserting that the election's outcome had been affected by hacking in those states; Stein did not provide evidence for her claims.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Changing the outcome of these three states would make Clinton the winner, and this would require showing that fewer than 60,000 votes had been counted for Trump which should have been counted for Clinton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Stein filed for a recount in Wisconsin on November 25, after which Clinton campaign general counsel Marc Elias said their campaign would join Stein's recount efforts in that state and possibly others "in order to ensure the process proceeds in a manner that is fair to all sides".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Stein subsequently filed for a recount in Pennsylvania on November 28, and in Michigan on November 30.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Concurrently, American Delta Party/Reform Party presidential candidate Rocky De La Fuente sought and was granted a partial recount in Nevada that was unrelated to Stein's efforts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] President-elect Donald Trump issued a statement denouncing Stein's Wisconsin recount request saying, "The people have spoken and the election is over".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump further commented that the recount "is a scam by the Green Party for an election that has already been conceded".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The Trump campaign and Republican Party officials moved to block Stein's three recount efforts through state and federal courts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Instead, they present speculative claims going to the vulnerability of the voting machinery—but not actual injury".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Meanwhile, the Wisconsin recount was allowed to continue as it was nearing completion and had uncovered no significant irregularities.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The recounts in Wisconsin and Nevada were completed on schedule, resulting in only minor changes to vote tallies.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A partial recount of Michigan ballot found some precinct imbalances in Detroit, which were corrected.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A subsequent state audit found no evidence of voter fraud and concluded that the mistakes, which were "almost entirely" caused by poll-worker mistakes attributed to poor training, did not impair "the ability of Detroit residents to cast a ballot and have their vote counted".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The overall outcome of the election remained unchanged by the recount efforts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Intense lobbying (in one case involving claims of harassment and death threats) and grass-roots campaigns were directed at various GOP electors of the United States Electoral College to convince a sufficient number of them (37) to not vote for Trump, thus precluding a Trump presidency.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Members of the Electoral College themselves started a campaign for other members to "vote their conscience for the good of America" in accordance with Alexander Hamilton's Federalist Paper No.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] On December 6, Colorado Secretary of State Wayne W.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Williams castigated Democratic electors who had filed a lawsuit in Federal court to have the state law binding them to the popular vote (in their case for Hillary Clinton) overturned.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] On December 10, ten electors, in an open letter headed by Christine Pelosi to the Director of National Intelligence James Clapper, demanded an intelligence briefing in light of Russian interference in the election to help Trump win the presidency.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Fifty-eight additional electors subsequently added their names to the letter, bringing the total to 68 electors from 17 different states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] On December 16, the briefing request was denied.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] On December 19, several electors voted against their pledged candidates: two against Trump and five against Clinton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A further three electors attempted to vote against Clinton but were replaced or forced to vote again.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The 115th United States Congress officially certified the results on January 6, 2017.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In the Electoral College vote on December 19, for the first time since the ratification of the 12th Amendment, multiple faithless electors voted against their pledged qualified presidential candidate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Five Democrats rebelled in Washington and Hawaii, while two Republicans rebelled in Texas.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Two Democratic electors, one in Minnesota and one in Colorado, were replaced after voting for Bernie Sanders and John Kasich, respectively.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Electors in Maine conducted a second vote after one of its members voted for Sanders; the elector then voted for Clinton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Likewise, for the first time since 1896, multiple faithless electors voted against the pledged qualified vice presidential candidate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Of the faithless votes, Colin Powell and Elizabeth Warren were the only two to receive more than one; Powell received three electoral votes for president and Warren received two for vice president.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Receiving one valid electoral vote each were Sanders, John Kasich, Ron Paul and Faith Spotted Eagle for president, and Carly Fiorina, Susan Collins, Winona LaDuke and Maria Cantwell for vice president.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Sanders is the first Jewish American to receive an electoral vote for president.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] LaDuke is the first Green Party member to receive an electoral vote, and Paul is the third member of the Libertarian Party to do so, following the party's presidential and vice-presidential nominees each getting one vote in 1972.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] It is the first election with faithless electors from more than one political party.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] On January 6, 2017, a Joint Session of Congress was held to count the Electoral College votes, pursuant to the Electoral Count Act.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This count was unusual for the many unsuccessful objections raised by Democratic members of the House of Representatives, alleging voter suppression and foreign interference.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Critics alleged racial bias after comparing the different sentences handed down to two white people and one black person who were convicted of attempting to vote illegally in the 2016 presidential election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] On December 9, 2016, the Central Intelligence Agency issued an assessment to lawmakers in the US Senate, stating that a Russian entity hacked the DNC and John Podesta's emails to assist Donald Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The Federal Bureau of Investigation agreed.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] President Barack Obama ordered a "full review" into such possible intervention.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Director of National Intelligence James R.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Clapper in early January 2017 testified before a Senate committee that Russia's meddling in the 2016 presidential campaign went beyond hacking, and included disinformation and the dissemination of fake news, often promoted on social media.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Facebook revealed that during the 2016 United States presidential election, a Russian company funded by Yevgeny Prigozhin, a Russian businessman with ties to Vladimir Putin, had purchased advertisements on the website for US$100,000, 25% of which were geographically targeted to the U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] President-elect Trump originally called the report fabricated.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Julian Assange said the Russian government was not the source of the documents.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Days later, Trump said he could be convinced of the Russian hacking "if there is a unified presentation of evidence from the Federal Bureau of Investigation and other agencies".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Several U.S. senators—including Republicans John McCain, Richard Burr, and Lindsey Graham—demanded a congressional investigation.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The Senate Intelligence Committee announced the scope of their bipartisan official inquiry on December 13, which began on January 24, 2017.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A formal Special Counsel investigation headed by former FBI director Robert Mueller was initiated in May 2017 to uncover the detailed interference operations by Russia, and to determine whether any people associated with the Trump campaign were complicit in the Russian efforts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] When questioned by Chuck Todd on *Meet the Press* in March 2017, Clapper declared that intelligence investigations on Russian interference performed by the FBI, CIA, NSA and his ODNI office had found no evidence of collusion between the Trump campaign and Russia.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Mueller concluded his investigation on March 22, 2019, by submitting his report to Attorney General William Barr.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] On March 24, 2019, Barr submitted a letter describing Mueller's conclusions, and on April 18, 2019, a redacted version of the Mueller report was released to the public.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] It concluded that Russian interference in the 2016 presidential election did occur "in sweeping and systematic fashion" and "violated U.S. criminal law".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The first method detailed in the final report was the usage of the Internet Research Agency, waging "a social media campaign that favored presidential candidate Donald J.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump and disparaged presidential candidate Hillary Clinton".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The Internet Research Agency also sought to "provoke and amplify political and social discord in the United States".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] As a result, the GRU obtained hundreds of thousands of hacked documents, and the GRU proceeded by arranging releases of damaging hacked material via the WikiLeaks organization and also GRU's personas "DCLeaks" and "Guccifer 2.0".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] They also investigated if members of the Trump campaign "coordinated" with Russia, using the definition of "coordination" as having "an agreement—tacit or express—between the Trump campaign and the Russian government on election interference".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Investigators further elaborated that merely having "two parties taking actions that were informed by or responsive to the other's actions or interests" was not enough to establish coordination.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Ultimately, "the investigation did not establish that members of the Trump campaign conspired or coordinated with the Russian government in its election interference activities".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] However, investigators had an incomplete picture of what had really occurred during the 2016 campaign, due to some associates of Trump campaign providing either false, incomplete or declined testimony, as well as having deleted, unsaved or encrypted communications.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] As such, the Mueller report "cannot rule out the possibility" that information then unavailable to investigators would have presented different findings.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In March 2020, the US Justice Department dropped its prosecution of two Russian firms linked to interference in the 2016 election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Special Council Robert Mueller also investigated the Trump campaign's alleged ties to Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Turkey, Qatar, Israel, and China.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The Justice Department accused George Nader of providing $3.5 million in illicit campaign donations to Hillary Clinton before the elections and to Trump after he won the elections.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] According to *The New York Times*, this was an attempt by the government of United Arab Emirates to influence the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In December 2018, a Ukrainian court ruled that prosecutors in Ukraine had meddled in the 2016 election by releasing damaging information on Trump campaign chairman Paul Manafort.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In July 2021, the US federal prosecutors accused Trump's former adviser Tom Barrack for being an unregistered foreign lobbying agent for the United Arab Emirates during the 2016 presidential campaign of Donald Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2016-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In 2022, Barrack was found not guilty on all charges.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-california-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Democratic Governor Jerry Brown was ineligible to run for a third consecutive term due to term limits.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-california-gubernatorial-election] The race was between the incumbent Democratic Lieutenant Governor Gavin Newsom and businessman John H.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-california-gubernatorial-election] Cox, a Republican, who qualified for the general election after placing first and second in the June 5, 2018 primary election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-california-gubernatorial-election] Newsom won in a landslide, with 62% of the vote, the biggest victory in a gubernatorial race in California since Earl Warren won re-election in 1950, and the biggest victory for a non-incumbent since 1930.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-california-gubernatorial-election] The election also marked the first time in 40 years since Orange County had voted for the Democratic candidate since Jerry Brown won it in 1978, and the first time Democrats won three consecutive gubernatorial elections in the state's history.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-california-gubernatorial-election] A primary election was held on June 5, 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-california-gubernatorial-election] Under California's non-partisan blanket primary law, all candidates appeared on the same ballot, regardless of party.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-california-gubernatorial-election] Voters may vote for any candidate, regardless of their party affiliation.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-california-gubernatorial-election] The top two finishers – regardless of party – advance to the general election in November, regardless of whether a candidate manages to receive a majority of the votes cast in the primary election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-california] The **2018 United States House of Representatives elections in California** were held on November 6, 2018, with the primary elections being held on June 5, 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-california] Voters elected the 53 U.S. representatives from the state of California, one from each of the state's 53 congressional districts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-california] The elections coincided with the elections of other offices, including a gubernatorial election, other elections to the House of Representatives, elections to the United States Senate, and various state and local elections.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-california] Democrats won in seven congressional districts previously represented by Republicans, all of which voted for Hillary Clinton in 2016.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-california] This reduced the California House Republican delegation by half and left the Republican Party with the fewest seats in California since just before the 1946 election cycle.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-california] Republican incumbents Jeff Denham, David Valadao, Steve Knight, Mimi Walters, and Dana Rohrabacher (who had been elected to fifteen terms) were all defeated.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-california] Democrats also picked up two open seats previously held by retiring GOP incumbents: thirteen-term incumbent Ed Royce and nine-term incumbent Darrell Issa.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-california] The seven Democratic House pickups in California were the most made by the party in the 2018 election cycle.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2018-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-california] Additionally, Democrats won all House seats in Orange County, traditionally a Republican bastion.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 3, 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic ticket of former vice president Joe Biden and California junior senator Kamala Harris defeated the incumbent Republican president Donald Trump and vice president Mike Pence.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The election saw the highest voter turnout by percentage since 1900.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Biden received more than 81 million votes, the most votes ever cast for a presidential candidate in U.S. history.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] In a competitive primary that featured the most candidates for any political party in the modern era of American politics, Biden secured the Democratic presidential nomination.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Biden's running mate, Harris, became the first African American, first Asian American, and third female vice presidential nominee on a major party ticket.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump easily secured re-nomination with only minor opposition in the Republican primaries.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Jo Jorgensen secured the Libertarian presidential nomination with Spike Cohen as her running mate, and Howie Hawkins secured the Green presidential nomination with Angela Nicole Walker as his running mate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Due to the ongoing pandemic, a record number of ballots were cast early and by mail.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Thirty-eight states had over half of all votes cast using these methods, and only three states had fewer than 25%.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] As a result of a large number of mail-in ballots, some swing states saw delays in vote counting and reporting; this led to major news outlets delaying their projection of Biden and Harris as the president-elect and vice president-elect until the morning of November 7, 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Biden defeated Trump, winning 306 Electoral College votes and 51.3% of the popular vote to Trump's 232 electoral votes and 46.8% of the popular vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump was the first president to lose re-election since George H.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Key to Biden's pivotal victory were his wins in the Democratic-leaning Rust Belt states of Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin, which Trump narrowly carried in 2016 and whose combined 46 electoral votes were enough to swing the election to either candidate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] This election marked the first time since 1948 that the Democratic Party won the popular vote in four consecutive elections.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump refused to accept the results; he and his allies made disproven claims of fraud, pressured election officials, filed several unsuccessful lawsuits, and directly attempted to overturn the results at the county, state, and federal level.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] This culminated in the attack on the United States Capitol, on January 6, 2021, for which Trump was impeached a second time.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The day after the attack, Trump stated that a "new administration" would be succeeding his, without mentioning president-elect Biden by name, in a video posted on Twitter.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The Maine Legislature passed a bill in August 2019 adopting ranked-choice voting (RCV) both for presidential primaries and for the general election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Governor Janet Mills allowed the bill to become law without her signature, which delayed its taking effect until after the 2020 Democratic primary in March and made Maine the first state to use RCV for a presidential general election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The Maine Republican Party filed signatures for a veto referendum to preclude the use of RCV for the 2020 election, but Secretary of State Matthew Dunlap found there were insufficient valid signatures to qualify for the ballot.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] A challenge in Maine Superior Court was successful for the Maine Republican Party, but the Maine Supreme Judicial Court stayed the ruling pending appeal on September 8, 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, ballots began being printed later that day without the veto referendum and including RCV for the presidential election, and the Court ruled in favor of the secretary of state on September 22, allowing RCV to be used.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] An emergency appeal to the Supreme Court was denied on October 6.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The law continues the use of the congressional district method for the allocation of Maine's electors (Nebraska is the only other state that apportions its electoral votes this way).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On December 14, 2020, pledged electors for each candidate, known collectively as the United States Electoral College, gathered in their states' capitols to cast their official votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Pursuant to the processes laid out by the Electoral Count Act of 1887, certificates of ascertainment listing the names of the electors and separate certificates recording their votes are distributed to various officials across the branches of government.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The newly elected Congress, with the vice president in his role as Senate president presiding, met in a joint session to formally open the certificates and count the votes, which began on January 6, 2021, was interrupted by the January 6 United States Capitol attack, and finished the following day.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic Party chose its nominee in the 2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Joe Biden became the presumptive nominee of the Democratic Party on April 8, 2020, after senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont withdrew from the race.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On June 5, 2020, Biden secured enough delegates to ensure his nomination at the national convention.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Biden picked Kamala Harris as his vice-presidential nominee, and the ticket was formally nominated at the convention on August 18.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent president Donald Trump and incumbent vice president Mike Pence were able to easily secure the nomination against former governor of Massachusetts Bill Weld after Trump received enough delegates in the 2020 Republican presidential primaries.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] They were formally nominated at the Republican National Convention on August 24, 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump won 2,549 delegates (out of 2,550), one of the most in presidential primary history.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Jo Jorgensen, who was the running mate of author Harry Browne in 1996, received the Libertarian nomination at the national convention on May 23, 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] She achieved ballot access in all 50 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Howie Hawkins became the presumptive nominee of the Green Party on June 21, 2020, and was officially nominated by the party on July 11, 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Hawkins secured ballot access in 29 states and the District of Columbia, representing 381 electoral votes, and write-in access in 16 more states, representing 130 electoral votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The 2020 Democratic National Convention was originally scheduled for July 13–16 in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, but was delayed to August 17–20 due to the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On June 24, 2020, it was announced that the convention would be held in a mixed online in-person format, with most delegates attending remotely but a few still attending the physical convention site.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On August 5, the in-person portion of the convention was scaled down even further; major speeches, including Biden's, were switched to a virtual format.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The 2020 Republican National Convention took place from August 24–27 in Charlotte, North Carolina, and various remote locations.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Due to the worsening situation with regards to COVID-19 in Florida, the plans there were cancelled, and the convention was moved back to Charlotte in a scaled-down capacity.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The 2020 Libertarian National Convention was originally scheduled to be held in Austin, Texas, over Memorial Day weekend from May 22 to 25, but all reservations at the JW Marriott Downtown Austin for the convention were cancelled on April 26 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The Libertarian National Committee eventually decided the party would hold two conventions, one online from May 22–24 to select the presidential and vice-presidential nominees and one at a physical convention in Orlando, Florida, from July 8–12 for other business.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The 2020 Green National Convention was originally to be held in Detroit, Michigan, from July 9 to 12.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the convention was instead held online, without a change in date.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The House of Representatives voted to impeach Trump on two counts on December 18, 2019.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The trial in the Senate began on January 21, 2020, and ended on February 5, resulting in acquittal by the United States Senate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] This is the second time a president has been impeached during his first term while running for a second term.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump continued to hold campaign rallies during the impeachment.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] This is also the first time since the modern presidential primaries were established in 1911 that a president has been subjected to impeachment while the primary season was underway.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The impeachment process overlapped with the primary campaigns, forcing senators running for the Democratic nomination to remain in Washington for the trial in the days before and after the Iowa caucuses.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Several events related to the 2020 presidential election were altered or postponed due to the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic in the United States and its effects, such as stay-at-home orders and social distancing guidelines by local governments.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On March 10, following primary elections in six states, Democratic candidates Joe Biden and Bernie Sanders cancelled planned campaign night events and further in-person campaigning and campaign rallies.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On March 12, Trump also stated his intent to postpone further campaign rallies.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The 11th Democratic debate was held on March 15 without an audience at the CNN studios in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Several states also postponed their primaries to a later date, including Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana, Ohio, and Maryland.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] As of March 24, 2020, all major-party presidential candidates had halted in-person campaigning and campaign rallies over COVID-19 concerns.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Political analysts speculated at the time that the moratorium on traditional campaigning, coupled with the effects of the pandemic on the nation, could have unpredictable effects on the voting populace and possibly, how the election will be conducted.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Some presidential primary elections were severely disrupted by COVID-19-related issues, including long lines at polling places, greatly increased requests for absentee ballots, and technology issues.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Due to a shortage of election workers able or willing to work during the pandemic, the number of polling places was often greatly reduced.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Most states expanded or encouraged voting by mail as an alternative, but many voters complained that they never received the absentee ballots they had requested.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The March 2020 Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act included money for states to increase mail-in voting.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] By May, Trump and his campaign strongly opposed mail-in voting, claiming that it would cause widespread voter fraud, a belief that has been discredited by a number of media organizations.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Government response to the impact of the pandemic from the Trump administration, coupled with the differing positions taken by congressional Democrats and Republicans regarding economic stimulus, became a major campaign issue for both parties.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On April 6, the Supreme Court and Republicans in the State Legislature of Wisconsin rebuffed Wisconsin governor Tony Evers's request to move the state's spring elections to June.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] As a result, the elections, which included a presidential primary, went ahead on April 7 as planned.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] At least seven new cases of COVID-19 were traced to this election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Voting-rights advocates expressed fear of similar chaos on a nationwide scale in November, recommending states move to expand vote-by-mail options.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On June 20, 2020, Trump's campaign held an in-person rally in Tulsa, Oklahoma, after the Oklahoma Supreme Court ruled that the event could go ahead despite continuing concerns over COVID-19.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Attendance at the rally was far lower than expected, being described as a "flop", and it led to a significant worsening of relations between Trump and his campaign manager, Brad Parscale.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] 7.7 million people watched the event on Fox News, a Saturday audience record for that channel.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Three weeks after the rally, the Oklahoma State Department of Health recorded record numbers of cases of COVID-19, and former Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain died of the virus, although it was not confirmed that he caught the disease due to his attendance at the rally.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On October 2, 2020, Trump and First Lady Melania Trump tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 following a positive test from his senior advisor, Hope Hicks, as part of the larger COVID-19 outbreak among White House personnel.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Both the president and first lady immediately entered quarantine, which prevented Trump from further campaigning, notably at campaign rallies.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Later that day, the President was admitted to Walter Reed National Military Medical Center with a low grade fever, where he was reported to have received an experimental antibody treatment.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump's diagnosis came only two days after he had shared the stage with Biden at the first presidential debate and raised the possibility that Biden had caught the virus from Trump; Biden tested negative.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump was discharged from the hospital on October 5.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump being diagnosed with COVID-19 was widely seen as having a negative effect on his campaign and shifted the attention of the public back onto COVID-19, an issue which is generally seen as a liability for Trump, due to his response to the COVID-19 pandemic suffering from low approval ratings.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Being in quarantine also meant Trump was unable to attend rallies, which were a major part of his campaign.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] As a result of Trump contracting COVID-19, Biden continued campaigning but temporarily ceased running attack ads against him.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On October 12, one week after his discharge from the hospital, Trump resumed in-person rallies.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump continued to travel to battleground states and hold mass rallies, sometimes two or three in a day.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] His rallies were criticized for their lack of social distancing or mask wearing, and some polls suggested that voters saw him less favorably for potentially endangering attendees.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] U.S. officials accused Russia, China, and Iran of trying to influence the 2020 United States elections.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On October 4, 2019, Microsoft announced that "Phosphorus", a group of hackers linked to the Iranian government, had attempted to compromise e-mail accounts belonging to journalists, U.S. government officials and the campaign of a U.S. presidential candidate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On February 13, 2020, American intelligence officials advised members of the House Intelligence Committee that Russia was interfering in the 2020 election in an effort to get Trump re-elected.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The briefing was delivered by Shelby Pierson, the intelligence community's top election security official and an aide to acting Director of National Intelligence Joseph Maguire.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On February 21, *The Washington Post* reported that, according to unnamed U.S. officials, Russia was interfering in the Democratic primary in an effort to support the nomination of Senator Bernie Sanders.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Sanders issued a statement after the news report, saying in part, "I don't care, frankly, who Putin wants to be president.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] My message to Putin is clear: stay out of American elections, and as president, I will make sure that you do." Sanders acknowledged that his campaign was briefed about Russia's alleged efforts about a month prior.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] China and some government-linked Chinese individuals have been accused of interfering in the election to support the candidacy of both Biden and Trump, though whether it is actually doing so is disputed among the intelligence community.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On October 21, threatening emails were sent to Democrats in at least four states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The emails warned, "You will vote for Trump on Election Day or we will come after you." Director of National Intelligence John Ratcliffe announced that evening that the emails, using a spoofed return address, had been sent by Iran.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] In his announcement, Ratcliffe said Iran's intent had been "to intimidate voters, incite social unrest, and damage President Trump", raising questions as to how ordering Democrats to vote for Trump would be damaging to Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] It was later reported that the reference to Trump had not been in Ratcliffe's prepared remarks as signed off by the other officials on the stage; he had added it on his own.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On November 18, 2021, the Justice Department charged two Iranian hackers with attempting to intimidate American voters ahead of the 2020 U.S. election by sending threatening emails and spreading false information.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Throughout the election period, several Colombian lawmakers and the Colombian ambassador to the United States issued statements supporting the Donald Trump campaign, which has been viewed as potentially harmful to Colombia–United States relations.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Ambassador to Colombia, Philip Goldberg, requested that Colombian politicians abstain from getting involved in the elections.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] During the campaign, Trump indicated in Twitter posts, interviews, and speeches that he might refuse to recognize the outcome of the election if he were defeated; Trump falsely suggested that the election would be rigged against him.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] In July 2020, Trump declined to answer whether he would accept the results, just as he did in the 2016 presidential election, telling Fox News anchor Chris Wallace that "I have to see.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] I'm not going to say no." Trump repeatedly claimed that "the only way" he could lose would be if the election was "rigged" and repeatedly refused to commit to a peaceful transition of power after the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump also attacked mail-in voting throughout the campaign, falsely claiming that the practice contains high rates of fraud; at one point, Trump said, "We'll see what happens ...
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Get rid of the ballots and you'll have a very peaceful—there won't be a transfer, frankly.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] There will be a continuation." Trump's statements have been described as a threat "to upend the constitutional order".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] In September 2020, FBI Director Christopher A.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Wray, who was appointed by Trump, testified under oath that the FBI has "not seen, historically, any kind of coordinated national voter fraud effort in a major election, whether it's by mail or otherwise".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] A number of congressional Republicans insisted they were committed to an orderly and peaceful transition of power, but declined to criticize Trump for his comments.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On September 24, the Senate unanimously passed a resolution affirming the Senate's commitment to a peaceful transfer of power.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump also stated he expected the Supreme Court to decide the election and that he wanted a conservative majority in case of an election dispute, reiterating his commitment to quickly install a ninth justice following the death of Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] In April 2020, Biden predicted that Trump would try to delay the election, saying he "is gonna try to kick back the election somehow, come up with some rationale why it can't be held".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] In May, Jared Kushner did not rule out delaying the election, saying "I'm not sure I can commit one way or the other".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On July 30, Trump tweeted that "With Universal Mail-In Voting (not Absentee Voting, which is good), 2020 will be the most INACCURATE & FRAUDULENT Election in history" and proposed that the election should be delayed.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Congress refused to consider Trump's proposal, and the election went ahead as scheduled.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Postal voting in the United States has become increasingly common, with 25% of voters mailing their ballots in 2016 and 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] By June 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic was predicted to cause a large increase in mail voting because of the possible danger of congregating at polling places.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] An August 2020 state-by-state analysis concluded that 76% of Americans were eligible to vote by mail in 2020, a record number.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The analysis predicted that 80 million ballots could be cast by mail in 2020—more than double the number in 2016.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The Postal Service sent a letter to multiple states in July 2020, warning that the service would not be able to meet the state's deadlines for requesting and casting last-minute absentee ballots.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On August 18, after the House of Representatives had been recalled from its August break to vote on a bill reversing the changes, DeJoy announced that he would roll back all the changes until after the November election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] He said he would reinstate overtime hours, roll back service reductions, and halt the removal of mail-sorting machines and collection boxes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The House of Representatives voted an emergency grant of $25 billion to the post office to facilitate the predicted flood of mail ballots.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Although Trump has repeatedly denounced mail voting, he has mailed in ballots due to being in a different state than the one where he votes at the time of the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] In August 2020, Trump conceded that the post office would need additional funds to handle the additional mail-in voting, but said he would block any additional funding for the post office to prevent any increase in balloting by mail.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] In the end, an estimated 42 percent of votes were cast by mail across 41 reporting states, approximately 65.6 million ballots out of 154.6 million cast by all methods.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The Trump campaign and the Republican Party both failed to produce any evidence of vote-by-mail fraud after being ordered by a federal judge to do so.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On Election Day, a judge ordered mail inspectors to search "mail facilities in .... key battleground states" for ballots.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The agency refused to comply with the order and nearly 7% of ballots in USPS facilities on Election Day were not processed in time.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The Federal Election Commission, which was created in 1974 to enforce campaign finance laws in federal elections, has not functioned since July 2020 due to vacancies in membership.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] In the absence of a quorum, the commission cannot vote on complaints or give guidance through advisory opinions.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] As of May 19, 2020, there were 350 outstanding matters on the agency's enforcement docket and 227 items waiting for action.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] As of September 1, 2020, Trump had not nominated anyone to fill the FEC vacancies.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On September 18, 2020, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg died.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell immediately said the precedent he had set regarding the Merrick Garland nomination was inoperative and that a replacement would be voted on as soon as possible, setting the stage for a confirmation battle and an unexpected intrusion into the campaign.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The death of Justice Ginsburg resulted in large increases in momentum for both the Democrats and Republicans.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The president, vice president, and several Republican members of Congress said a full Supreme Court bench was needed to decide the upcoming election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On September 26, the day after Justice Ginsburg's body lay in state at the Capitol, Trump held a Rose Garden ceremony at the White House to announce and introduce his candidate, Amy Coney Barrett.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] After four days of confirmation hearings, the Senate Judiciary Committee voted the nomination out of committee on October 22, and on October 26, Barrett was confirmed on a party-line vote of 52–48, with no Democrats voting for her confirmation.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] This was the closest Supreme Court confirmation ever to a presidential election, and the first Supreme Court nomination since 1869 with no supporting votes from the minority party.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] It was also one of the fastest timelines from nomination to confirmations in U.S. history.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] By September 2020, several hundred legal cases relating to the election had been filed.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] About 250 of these had to do with the mechanics of voting in relation to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The Supreme Court ruled on a number of these cases, primarily issuing emergency stays instead of going through the normal process due to the urgency.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] In October 2020, there was speculation that the election might be decided through a Supreme Court case, as happened following the 2000 election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On October 11, 2019, the Commission on Presidential Debates (CPD) announced that three general election debates would be held in the fall of 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The first, moderated by Chris Wallace, took place on September 29, and was co-hosted by Case Western Reserve University and the Cleveland Clinic in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The debate was originally to be hosted at the University of Notre Dame in Notre Dame, Indiana, but the university decided against holding the debate as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Biden was generally held to have won the first debate, with a significant minority of commentators deeming it a draw.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] One exchange that was particularly noted was when Trump did not directly denounce the white supremacist and neo-fascist group Proud Boys, instead responding that they should "stand back and stand by".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] On the next day, Trump told reporters the group should "stand down" while also claiming that he was not aware of what the group was.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The debate was described as "chaotic and nearly incoherent" because of Trump's repeated interruptions, causing the CPD to consider adjustments to the format of the remaining debates.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The vice presidential debate was held on October 7, 2020, at the University of Utah in Salt Lake City.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The debate was widely held to be subdued, with no clear victor.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] One incident that was particularly commented on was when a fly landed on vice-president Pence's head, and remained there unbeknownst to him for two minutes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The second debate was initially set to be held at the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor, Michigan, but the university withdrew in June 2020, over concerns regarding the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The planned debate was rescheduled for October 15 at the Adrienne Arsht Center for the Performing Arts in Miami; due to Trump contracting COVID-19, the CPD announced on October 8 that the debate would be held virtually, in which the candidates would appear from separate locations.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Trump refused to participate in a virtual debate, and the commission subsequently announced that the debate had been cancelled.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The third scheduled debate took place on October 22 at Belmont University in Nashville, Tennessee, and was moderated by Kristen Welker.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The changes to the debate rules, which included the candidates' microphones being muted while the other was speaking, resulted in it being generally considered more civil than the first debate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Welker's performance as moderator was praised, with her being regarded as having done a good job preventing the candidates from interrupting each other.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Biden was generally held to have won the debate, though it was considered unlikely to alter the race to any considerable degree.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The Free & Equal Elections Foundation held two debates with various third party and independent candidates, one on October 8, 2020, in Denver, Colorado, and another on October 24, 2020, in Cheyenne, Wyoming.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The following graph depicts the standing of each candidate in the poll aggregators from September 2019 to November 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Former Vice President Joe Biden, the Democratic nominee, had an average polling lead of 7.9 percentage points over incumbent President Donald Trump, the Republican nominee.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Biden would win the national popular vote by 4.4 percentage points.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] Calculated averages are not comparable to those for the Biden vs.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] As polling with third parties has been very limited, the polls included in the average are often different.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] The following graph depicts the difference between Joe Biden and Donald Trump in each swing state in the poll aggregators from March 2020 to the election, with the election results for comparison.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p01] OpenSecrets estimated the total cost of the 2020 election nearly $14 billion, making it the most expensive election in history and twice as expensive as the previous presidential election cycle.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic was a major issue of the campaign, with Trump's responses being heavily criticized.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] The president spread mixed messages on the value of wearing face masks as protection, including criticizing Biden and reporters for wearing them, but has also encouraged their use at times.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] During the campaign, Trump held many events across the country, including in COVID-19 hotspots, where attendees did not wear masks and were not socially distancing; at the same time, he mocked those who wore face masks.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden advocated for the expansion of federal funding, including funding under the Defense Production Act for testing, personal protective equipment, and research.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump also invoked the Defense Production Act to control the distribution of masks and ventilators, but his response plan relied significantly on a vaccine being released by the end of 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] At the second presidential debate, Trump claimed Biden had called him xenophobic for restricting entry from foreign nationals who had visited China, but Biden responded that he had not been referring to this decision.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump claimed credit for the consistent economic expansion of his presidency's first three years, with the stock market at its longest growth period in history and unemployment at a fifty-year low.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Additionally, he has touted the 2020 third-quarter rebound, in which GDP grew at an annualized rate of 33.1%, as evidence of the success of his economic policies.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden responded to Trump's claims by repeating that the strong economy under Trump's presidency was inherited from the Obama administration, and that Trump has aggravated the economic impact of the pandemic, including the need for 42 million Americans to file for unemployment.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, which lowered income taxes for many Americans and lowered the corporate tax rate from 35% to 21%, were a major component of Trump's economic policy.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden and the Democrats generally describe these cuts as unfairly benefiting the upper class.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden plans to raise taxes on corporations and those making over $400,000 per year, while keeping the reduced taxes on lower-income brackets and raise capital gains taxes to a maximum bracket of 39.6%.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] In response, Trump said Biden's plans would destroy retirement accounts and the stock market.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump and Biden's views on environmental policy differ significantly.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump stated that climate change is a hoax, although he also called it a serious subject.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump condemned the Paris Agreement on greenhouse gas reduction and began the withdrawal process.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden planned to rejoin it and announced a $2 trillion plan to combat climate change.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden had not fully accepted the Green New Deal.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden did not plan to ban fracking but rather to outlaw new fracking on federal land.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] In a debate, Trump claimed Biden wanted to ban it altogether.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump's other environmental policies included the removal of methane emission standards, and an expansion of mining.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Health care was a divisive issue in both the Democratic primary campaign and the general campaign.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] While Biden, as well as other candidates, promised protection of the Affordable Care Act, progressives within the Democratic Party advocated to replace the private insurance industry with Medicare for All.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden's plan involves adding a public option to the American healthcare system, and the restoration of the individual mandate to buy health care, which was removed from the Affordable Care Act by the 2017 tax cut bill, as well as restoring funding for Planned Parenthood.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump announced plans to repeal the Affordable Care Act, calling it "too expensive", but he did not say what would replace it.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] At the time of the election, the Trump administration and Republican officials from 18 states had a lawsuit before the Supreme Court, asking the court to repeal the Affordable Care Act.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] As a result of the murder of George Floyd and other incidents of police brutality against African Americans, combined with the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic, a series of protests and a wider period of racial unrest erupted in mid-2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] This was followed by the Black Lives Matter movement, which protested police brutality against black people, and became a central point of the 2020 presidential campaign.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Protests were mostly peaceful; fewer than 4% involved property damage or violence (with most of the latter directed at BLM protesters themselves).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] According to a September 2020 estimate, arson, vandalism, and looting caused about $1–2 billion in insured damage between May 26 and June 8, making this initial phase of the George Floyd protests the civil disorder event with the highest recorded damage in United States history.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] In response, Trump and the Republicans suggested sending in the military to counter the protests, which was criticized, especially by Democrats, as heavy-handed and potentially illegal.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump referred to Black Lives Matter protesters confronting diners in a restaurant as "thugs", and called a street painting of the slogan a "symbol of hate".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Particularly controversial was a photo-op Trump took in front of St.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] John's Church in Washington, D.C., before which military police had forcefully cleared peaceful protestors from the area.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden condemned Trump for his actions against protestors; he described George Floyd's words "I can't breathe" as a "wake-up call for our nation".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] He also promised he would create a police oversight commission in his first 100 days as president, and establish a uniform use of force standard, as well as other police reform measures.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] More than 158 million votes were cast in the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] More than 100 million of them were cast before Election Day by early voting or mail ballot, due to the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] The election saw the highest voter turnout as a percentage of eligible voters since 1900, with each of the two main tickets receiving more than 74 million votes, surpassing Barack Obama's record of 69.5 million votes in 2008.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] The Biden–Harris ticket received more than 81 million votes, the most votes ever in a U.S. presidential election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] In 2020, 58 percent of U.S. voters lived in landslide counties, a decline from 61 percent in 2016.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump became the 11th incumbent in the country's history, and the first since 1992, to lose a bid for a second term.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden's 51.3% of the popular vote was the highest for a challenger to an incumbent president since 1932.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden is the sixth vice president to become president without succeeding to the office on the death or resignation of a previous president.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Additionally, Trump's loss marked the third time an elected president lost the popular vote twice, the first being John Quincy Adams in the 1820s and Benjamin Harrison in the 1880s and 1890s.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] This was the first time since 1980, and the first for Republicans since 1892 that a party was voted out after a single four-year term.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] This was the second election in American history in which the incumbent president lost re-election despite winning a greater share of the popular vote than he did in the previous election, after 1828.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] It is also the third election in which the two candidates that received electoral votes carried the same number of states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden won 25 states, the District of Columbia, and one congressional district in Nebraska, totaling 306 electoral votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump won 25 states and one congressional district in Maine, totaling 232 electoral votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] This result was exactly the reverse of Trump's victory, 306 to 232, in 2016 (excluding faithless electors).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden became the first Democrat to win the presidential election in Georgia since 1992 and in Arizona since 1996, and the first candidate to win nationally without Florida since 1992 and Ohio since 1960, casting doubt on Ohio's continued status as a bellwether state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden also became the first Democrat to win the presidential election without Iowa since 1976.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden carried five states won by Trump in 2016: Arizona, Georgia, Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Despite his relatively comfortable 74 vote margin in the Electoral College, Biden only won the decisive states of Wisconsin, Georgia and Arizona by a combined 43,000 votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] He also became the first Democrat since 2008 to carry Nebraska's 2nd congressional district, winning one electoral vote from the state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Trump did not win any states won by Clinton in 2016.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Nevertheless, amidst Trump's national and electoral defeat, his scoring decisive victories in Ohio, Iowa, and Florida for the second time, after their having backed Obama twice, has led many commentators to conclude they have shifted from perennial swing states to reliable red states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] This situation paralleled 2016, when a shift of 0.77% or less in each of the three most closely contested states (Wisconsin, Michigan, and Pennsylvania), or about 77,000 votes, would have resulted in the popular vote winner Hillary Clinton also winning in the Electoral College.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] This was the first time since 1948 that Democrats won the popular vote in four elections in a row.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden was the second former vice president (after Richard Nixon in 1968) to win the presidency, as well as the first vice president since George H.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Almost all counties previously considered reliable indicators of eventual success in presidential elections voted for Trump instead of Biden, meaning that they did not continue their streaks as bellwether counties.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] This was attributed to increasing political polarization throughout the country and to the urban-rural divide.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] While Trump still dominated rural America as a whole, there were rural areas that he lost.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden won 50.5% of the rural counties that each had mostly non-white voters, particularly in the South and the West.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Rural counties in the South won by Biden had greater economic distress than those won by Trump; in the Northeast, the opposite was true.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] In the West, Biden did especially well in rural counties that had high shares of workers employed in leisure and hospitality.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Such counties likewise had large constituencies of immigration from other states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] At age 77, Biden was the oldest non-incumbent ever to win a presidential election, surpassing Trump's record in 2016, who was first elected at age 70.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Biden was also the oldest president ever elected, surpassing Ronald Reagan's record in 1984, who was re-elected at age 73.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Four years later, in 2024, Trump surpassed both records at age 78.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Of the 3,153 counties/districts/independent cities making returns, Trump won the most popular votes in 2,595 (82.30%) while Biden carried 558 (17.70%).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Major news organizations project a state for a candidate when there is high mathematical confidence that the outstanding vote would be unlikely to prevent the projected winner from ultimately winning the state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Election projections are made by decision teams of political scientists and data scientists.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] In the early hours of November 4, the Associated Press called Florida for Donald Trump at 12:35 a.m.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] EST, putting him at 164 electoral votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] EST, they called Texas for Trump, putting him at 202 electoral votes, compared to Joe Biden's 224.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Arizona and Maine were called for Biden at 2:51 a.m. and 3:06 a.m.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] EST that afternoon, the Associated Press called Maine's 2nd congressional district for Trump, giving him 203 electoral votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Then, Biden won Wisconsin and Michigan, at 2:16 p.m. and 3:58 p.m.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] EST, respectively, bringing him to 264 electoral votes, just 6 short of the presidency.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] On the morning of November 7 at approximately 11:25 a.m.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] That evening, Biden and Harris gave their victory speeches in Wilmington, Delaware.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, it was scaled down to a "limited election observation mission" from the originally planned 100 long-term observers and 400 short-term observers.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Link said that "on the election day itself, we couldn't see any violations" at the polling places visited by the observers.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] The task force also found "nothing untoward" while observing the handling of mail-in ballots at post offices, with Gacek being quoted as saying: "We feel that allegations of systemic wrongdoing in these elections have no solid ground.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] The system has held up well." The OSCE's election monitoring branch published a more comprehensive report in early 2021.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Candidates are listed individually below if they received more than 0.1% of the popular vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Popular vote totals are from the Federal Election Commission report.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Two states, Maine and Nebraska, allow their electoral votes to be split between candidates by congressional districts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] The winner of each congressional district gets one electoral vote for the district.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p02] Blue denotes states or congressional districts won by Democrat Joe Biden; red denotes those won by Republican Donald Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Voter demographic data for 2020 were collected by Edison Research for the National Election Pool, a consortium of ABC News, CBS News, MSNBC, CNN, Fox News, and the Associated Press.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] The voter survey is based on exit polls completed by 15,590 voters in person as well as by phone.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] The Brookings Institution released a report entitled "Exit polls show both familiar and new voting blocs sealed Biden's win" on November 12, 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Frey attributes Obama's 2008 win to young people, people of color, and the college-educated.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Frey contends Trump won in 2016 thanks to older White without college degrees.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Frey says the same coalitions largely held in 2008 and 2016, although in key battleground states Biden increased his vote among some of the 2016 Trump groups, particularly among White and older Americans.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Trump won the white vote in 2016 by 20% but in 2020 by only 16%.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] The Democratic Party won black voters by 75%, the lowest margin since 1980.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Democrats won the Latino vote by 32%, which is the smallest margin since 2004, and they won the Asian American vote by 27%, the lowest figure since 2008.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Biden reduced the Republican margin of white men without college educations from 48% to 42%, and the Democrats made a slight improvement of 2% among white, college-educated women.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] People age 18 to 29 registered a rise in Democratic support between 2016 and 2020, with the Democratic margin of victory among that demographic increasing from 19% to 24%.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] However, Baby boomers and Generation X still constituted the majority of the voting public.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] The exit poll estimated that voters 40 years of age or older (born in 1980 or earlier to comprise 68% of the electorate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Voters from age 40 through age 64 (born from 1956 through 1980) alone were estimated to comprise 46% of the electorate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Post-election analysis using verified voter data found the Associated Press's Votecast was more accurate than the exit polls.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Biden won 65% of the Latino vote according to Edison Research, and 63% according to the Associated Press.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Voto Latino reported that the Latino vote was crucial to the Biden victory in Arizona.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] 40% of Latino voters who voted in 2020 did not vote in 2016, and 73% of those Latino voters voted for Biden (438,000 voters).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Florida and Texas, which have large Latino populations, were carried by Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] In Florida, Trump won a majority of Cuban American voters in Miami-Dade County, Florida.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] The Latino vote was still crucial to enable Biden to carry states such as Nevada.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Latino voters were targeted by a major Spanish-language disinformation campaign in the final weeks of the election, with various falsehoods and conspiracy theories being pushed out by WhatsApp and viral social media posts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Demographic patterns emerged having to do with country of origin and candidate preference.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Pre- and post-election surveys showed Biden winning Latinos of Mexican, Puerto Rican, Dominican, Spanish, and Nuevomexicano heritage, while Trump carried Latinos of Cuban heritage.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Data from Florida showed Biden holding a narrow edge among South Americans.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Biden won 87% of the Black vote, while Trump won 12%.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Biden's advantage among Black voters was crucial in the large cities of Pennsylvania and Michigan; the increase in the Democratic vote in Milwaukee County of about 28,000 votes was more than the 20,000-vote lead Biden had in the state of Wisconsin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Almost half Biden's gains in Georgia came from the four largest counties—Fulton, DeKalb, Gwinnett, and Cobb—all in the Atlanta metro area with large Black populations.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Trump improved his overall share of the Black vote from 2016 by 4% and doubled the Black vote that Mitt Romney received in 2012.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Polls showed that 68% of Asian American and Pacific Island (AAPI) voters supported Biden/Harris, while 28% supported Trump/Pence.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Karthick Ramakrishnan, a political science professor at the University of California Riverside and founder of AAPI Data, said Asian Americans supported Biden over Trump by about a 2:1 margin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Korean Americans, Japanese Americans, Indian Americans, and Chinese Americans favored Biden by higher margins overall compared to Vietnamese Americans and Filipino Americans.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Data from FiveThirtyEight indicated 65% of Indian American voters backed Joe Biden, and 28% supported Donald Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Some Indian Americans self-identified with Kamala Harris, but others approved of Donald Trump's support of Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] In a speech given to 50,000 Indian-Americans during his 2019 visit to the US, Modi praised Trump with remarks that were interpreted as an indirect endorsement of his candidacy.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Indian right-wing organizations like the Hindu Sena had performed special havans and pujas for Trump's electoral victory.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Pre-election voter surveys by Indian Country Today found 68% of American Indian and Alaska Native voters supporting Democratic nominee Joe Biden.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] In particular, the Navajo Reservation, which spans a large quadrant of eastern Arizona and western New Mexico, delivered up to 97% of their votes per precinct to Biden, while overall support for Biden was between 60 and 90% on the Reservation.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Biden also posted large turnout among Havasupai, Hopi, and Tohono O'odham peoples, delivering a large win in New Mexico and flipping Arizona.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] In Montana, while the state went for Trump overall, Biden won counties overlapping reservations of the Blackfeet, Fort Belknap, Crow and Northern Cheyenne.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] The same pattern held in South Dakota, with most of the counties overlapping the lands of the Standing Rock Sioux, Cheyenne River Sioux, Oglala Sioux, Rosebud Sioux and Crow Creek tribes going for Biden.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] For example, in Oglala Lakota County, which overlaps with the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation, Biden won 88% of the vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Trump's strongest performance among Native tribes was with the Lumbee Tribe of North Carolina, where he won a strong majority in Robeson County and flipped Scotland County from Democratic to Republican.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Trump had campaigned in Lumberton, in Robeson County, and had promised the Lumbees federal recognition.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Although polls generally predicted the Biden victory, the national polls overestimated him by three to four points, and some state polling was even further from the actual result and greater than 2016's error (one or two points).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] The numbers represented the highest level of error since the 1980 presidential election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] This polling overestimation also applied in several Senate races, where the Democrats underperformed by about five points relative to the polls, as well as the House elections, where Republicans gained seats instead of losing as polls predicted.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Most pollsters underestimated support for Trump in several key battleground states, including Florida, Iowa, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Michigan, Texas, and Wisconsin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] The discrepancy between poll predictions and the actual result persisted from the 2016 election despite pollsters' attempts to fix problems with polling in 2016, in which they underestimated the Republican vote in several states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] The imprecise polls led to changes in campaigning and fundraising decisions for both Democrats and Republicans.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] According to CNN, research presented to the American Association for Public Opinion Research indicated one of the primary problems was an inability by pollsters to include a certain segment of Trump supporters, either due to inaccessibility or lack of participation.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] *New Statesman* data journalist Ben Walker pointed to Hispanics as a historically difficult group to poll accurately, leading to pollsters underestimating the level of Trump support within the demographic group.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p03] Election analyst Nate Silver of *FiveThirtyEight* argued that the polling error in 2020 was normal by historical standards.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Election night, November 3, ended without a clear winner, as many state results were too close to call and millions of votes remained uncounted, including in the battleground states of Wisconsin, Michigan, Pennsylvania, North Carolina, Georgia, Arizona, and Nevada.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Results were delayed in these states due to local rules on counting mail-in ballots.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Mail-in ballots became particularly prevalent in the 2020 election due to the widespread outbreak of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Over roughly 67 million mail-in ballots were submitted, over doubling the previous election's 33.5 million.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In a victory declared after midnight, Trump won the swing state of Florida by over three percentage points, an increase from his 1.2 percentage point margin in 2016, having seen significant gains in support among the Latino community in Miami-Dade County.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] EST, Biden made a short speech in which he urged his supporters to be patient while the votes are counted, and said he believed he was "on track to win this election".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] EST, Trump made a speech to a roomful of supporters, falsely asserting that he had won the election and calling for a stop to all vote counting, saying that continued counting was "a fraud on the American people" and "we will be going to the U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Supreme Court." The Biden campaign denounced these attempts, claiming the Trump campaign was engaging in a "naked effort to take away the democratic rights of American citizens".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In Pennsylvania, where the counting of mail-in ballots began on election night, Trump prematurely declared victory on November 4 with a lead of 675,000 votes, despite more than a million ballots remaining uncounted.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Trump also declared victory in North Carolina and Georgia, despite many ballots being uncounted.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] EST on election night, Fox News projected Biden would win Arizona, with the Associated Press making the same call at 2:50 a.m.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] EST on November 4; several other media outlets concluded the state was too close to call.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] By the evening of November 4, the Associated Press reported that Biden had secured 264 electoral votes by winning Michigan and Wisconsin, with Pennsylvania, North Carolina, Georgia, and Nevada remaining uncalled.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Biden had a 1% lead in Nevada and maintained a 2.3% lead in Arizona by November 5, needing only to win Nevada and Arizona or to win Pennsylvania to obtain the necessary 270 electoral votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Some Trump supporters expressed concerns of possible fraud after seeing the president leading in some states on Election Night, only to see Biden take the lead in subsequent days.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On November 5, a federal judge dismissed a lawsuit by the Trump campaign to stop vote-counting in Pennsylvania.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The Trump campaign had alleged that its observers were not given access to observe the vote, but its lawyers admitted during the hearing that its observers were already present in the vote-counting room.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Also that day, a state judge dismissed another lawsuit by the Trump campaign which alleged that in Georgia, late-arriving ballots were counted.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The judge ruled no evidence had been produced that the ballots were late.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Meanwhile, a state judge in Michigan dismissed the Trump campaign's lawsuit requesting a pause in vote-counting to allow access to observers, as the judge noted that vote-counting had already finished in Michigan.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] That judge also noted the official complaint did not state "why", "when, where, or by whom" an election observer was allegedly blocked from observing ballot-counting in Michigan.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On November 6, Biden assumed leads in Pennsylvania and Georgia as the states continued to count ballots, and absentee votes in those states heavily favored Biden.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Due to the slim margin between Biden and Trump in the state, Georgia Secretary of State Brad Raffensperger announced on November 6 that a recount would be held in Georgia.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] At that point, Georgia had not seen "any widespread irregularities" in this election, according to the voting system manager of the state, Gabriel Sterling.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Supreme Court Justice Samuel Alito issued an order requiring officials in Pennsylvania to segregate late-arriving ballots, amid a dispute as to whether the state's Supreme Court validly ordered a 3-day extension of the deadline for mail-in ballots to arrive.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Several Republican attorneys general filed amicus briefs before the U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Supreme Court in subsequent days agreeing with the Pennsylvania Republican Party's view that only the state legislature could change the voting deadline.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] According to CNN, people close to Donald Trump, such as his son-in-law and senior adviser Jared Kushner and his wife Melania Trump, urged him to accept his defeat.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] While Donald Trump privately acknowledged the outcome of the presidential election, he nonetheless encouraged his legal team to continue pursuing legal challenges.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Trump expected to win the election in Arizona, but when Fox News declared Biden the victor of the state, Trump became furious and claimed the result was due to fraud.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Trump and his allies suffered approximately 50 legal losses in four weeks after starting their litigation.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In view of these legal defeats, Trump began to employ "a public pressure campaign on state and local Republican officials to manipulate the electoral system on his behalf".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Protests against Trump's challenges to the election results occurred in Minneapolis, Portland, New York, and other cities.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Police in Minneapolis arrested more than 600 demonstrators for blocking traffic on an interstate highway.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In Portland, the National Guard was called out after some protesters smashed windows and threw objects at police.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] At the same time, groups of Trump supporters gathered outside of election centers in Phoenix, Detroit, and Philadelphia, shouting objections to counts that showed Biden leading or gaining ground.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Trump and a variety of his surrogates and supporters made a series of observably false claims that the election was fraudulent.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Claims that substantial fraud was committed have been repeatedly debunked.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On November 9 and 10, *The New York Times* called the offices of top election officials in every state; all 45 of those who responded said there was no evidence of fraud.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Some described the election as remarkably successful considering the coronavirus pandemic, the record turnout, and the unprecedented number of mailed ballots.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] As ballots were still being counted two days after Election Day, Trump falsely asserted that there was "tremendous corruption and fraud going on", adding: "If you count the legal votes, I easily win.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] If you count the illegal votes, they can try to steal the election from us." Trump has repeatedly claimed as suspicious that mail-in ballots showed significantly more support for Biden.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] This blue shift phenomenon is believed to occur because more Democrats than Republicans tend to vote by mail, and mail ballots are counted after Election Day in many states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Leading up to the 2020 election, the effect was predicted to be even greater than usual, as Trump's attacks on mail-in voting may have deterred Republicans from casting mail ballots.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In early January 2021, Trump falsely proclaimed that he had by rights won all 50 states in the presidential election and a 535 to 3 electoral college victory.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On January 2, during his phone call to Brad Raffensperger, the Georgia Secretary of State, Trump said, "As you know, every single state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] We won every state; we won every statehouse in the country...
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] But we won every single statehouse." Two days later, on January 4, Trump appeared at a campaign rally in Dalton, Georgia, supporting Republican senators David Perdue and Kelly Loeffler.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Many claims of purported voter fraud were discovered to be false or misleading.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In Fulton County, Georgia, the number of votes affected was 342, with no breakdown of which candidates they were for.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Another video of a poll watcher being turned away in Philadelphia was found to be real, but the poll watcher had subsequently been allowed inside after a misunderstanding had been resolved.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] A viral tweet claimed 14,000 votes in Wayne County, Michigan, were cast by dead people, but the list of names included was found to be incorrect.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The Trump campaign and Fox News commentator Tucker Carlson also claimed a man named James Blalock had voted in Georgia despite having died in 2006, but in fact his 94-year-old widow had registered and voted as Mrs.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In Erie, Pennsylvania, a postal worker who claimed the postmaster had instructed postal workers to backdate ballots mailed after Election Day later admitted he had fabricated the claim.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Prior to this recantation, Republican senator Lindsey Graham cited the claim in a letter to the Justice Department calling for an investigation, and a GoFundMe page created for the postal worker "patriot" raised $136,000.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Days after Biden had been declared the winner, White House press secretary Kayleigh McEnany asserted without evidence that the Democratic Party was welcoming fraud and illegal voting.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Responding to Giuliani, a spokesperson for Pennsylvania Attorney General Josh Shapiro said: "Many of the claims against the commonwealth have already been dismissed, and repeating these false attacks is reckless.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Attorneys who brought accusations of voting fraud or irregularities before judges could not produce valid evidence to support the allegations.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Some senior attorneys at law firms working for Trump, notably Jones Day, expressed concerns that they were undermining the integrity of American elections by advancing arguments without evidence.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Defamatory rumors about the company circulated on social media, amplified by more than a dozen tweets or retweets by Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The disinformation campaign prompted threats and harassment against Dominion employees.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] A December 2020 poll showed 77% of Republicans believed widespread fraud occurred during the election, along with 35% of independent voters.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Overall, 60% of Americans believed Biden's win was legitimate, 34% did not, and 6% were unsure.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Another poll taken in late December showed a similar result, with 62% of Americans polled believing Biden was the legitimate winner of the election, while 37% did not.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] This split in popular opinion remained largely stable, with a January 10, 2021, poll commissioned by ABC News showing 68% of Americans believed Biden's win was legitimate and 32% did not.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] These numbers remained largely stagnant, with a June 2021 poll from Monmouth showing 61% believed Biden won fair and square, 32% believed he won due to fraud, and 7% were unsure.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] More than a year later, public opinion on the matter still remained stagnant, with a poll commissioned by ABC News finding that 65% of Americans believed Biden's win was legitimate, 33% believed it was not legitimate, and 2% were unsure.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The same poll also found that 72% of Americans thought the people involved in the attack on the U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Capitol on January 6, 2021, were attacking democracy, while 25% thought they were protecting democracy, and 3% were unsure.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] A March 2022 poll commissioned by the conservative Rasmussen Reports found that 52% of voters think that it is likely that cheating "affected the outcome of the 2020 presidential election." while 40% of voters believe that it is unlikely.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] 33% say that cheating was very likely, 19% say it was somewhat likely, 13% say it was somewhat unlikely, and 27% say it was very unlikely.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Motivated by the myth of widespread fraud, Republican state lawmakers initiated a push to make voting laws more restrictive.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On December 13, 2024, just over a month after the 2024 United States presidential election, the Public Religion Research Institute published the results of a survey conducted shortly after that election, between November 8 and December 2.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The survey focused primarily on the 2024 election but included questions about the claim that the 2020 election was stolen from Trump: 63 percent of Republicans and 31 percent of voters overall still agreed that the 2020 election had been stolen from Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] After the election, the Trump campaign filed lawsuits in multiple states, including Georgia, Michigan, Nevada, and Pennsylvania.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Lawyers and other observers noted the suits were unlikely to affect the outcome.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Loyola Law School professor Justin Levitt said, "There's literally nothing that I've seen yet with the meaningful potential to affect the final result." Some law firms moved to drop their representation in lawsuits challenging results of the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Trump unsuccessfully sought to overturn Biden's win in Georgia through litigation; suits by the Trump campaign and allies were rejected by both the Georgia Supreme Court and by federal courts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Trump also sought to overturn Biden's win by pressuring Kemp to call a special session of the Georgia General Assembly so state legislators could override the Georgia election results and appoint a pro-Trump slate of electors, an entreaty rebuffed by Kemp.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On December 20, Giuliani filed a petition with the U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Supreme Court, asking them to overturn the results of the Pennsylvania election and direct the state legislature to appoint electors.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The Supreme Court was regarded as very unlikely to grant this petition, and in any case Biden would still have a majority of Electoral College votes without Pennsylvania.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The Court set the deadline for reply briefs from the respondents for January 22, 2021, two days after President Elect Biden's inauguration.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On December 9, Ken Paxton, the Attorney General of Texas, filed a lawsuit in the Supreme Court, asking the court to overturn the results in Michigan, Pennsylvania, Wisconsin, and Georgia.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Attorneys general of seventeen other states also signed onto the lawsuit.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In the House of Representatives, 126 Republicans—more than two-thirds of the Republican caucus—signed an amicus brief in support of the lawsuit.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The suit was rejected by the Supreme Court on December 11, due to a lack of standing.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Early in the morning on November 4, with vote counts still going on in many states, Trump claimed he had won: "This is an embarrassment to our country.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] We were getting ready to win this election, frankly we did win this election." For weeks after the networks had called the election for Biden, Trump refused to acknowledge that Biden had won.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Unlike every losing major party presidential candidate before him, Trump refused to formally concede, breaking with the tradition of formal concession started in 1896, when William Jennings Bryan sent a congratulatory telegram to President-elect William McKinley.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Biden described Trump's refusal as "an embarrassment".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In the wake of the election, Trump's White House ordered government agencies not to cooperate with the Biden transition team in any way, and the General Services Administration (GSA) refused to formally acknowledge Biden's victory.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Trump finally acknowledged Biden's victory in a tweet on November 15, although he refused to concede and blamed his loss on fraud, stating: "He won because the Election was Rigged." Trump then tweeted: "I concede NOTHING!
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Although all major media outlets called the election for Biden on November 7, the head of the General Services Administration (GSA), Trump appointee Emily W.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Murphy, refused for over two weeks to certify Biden as the president-elect.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Without formal GSA ascertainment of the winner, the official transition process was delayed.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On November 23, Murphy acknowledged Biden as the winner and said the Trump administration would begin the transition.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Trump said he had instructed his administration to "do what needs to be done" but did not concede, and indicated he would continue his fight to overturn the election results.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In November, Trump focused his efforts on trying to delay vote certifications at the county and state level.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On December 2, Trump posted a 46-minute video to his social media in which he repeated his baseless claims that the election was "rigged" and fraudulent, and he called for either state legislatures or courts to overturn the election and allow him to stay in office.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] He continued to pressure elected Republicans in Michigan, Georgia, and Pennsylvania in an unprecedented attempt to overturn his loss.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Some commentators have characterized Trump's actions as an attempted coup d'état or self-coup.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] A December 18 meeting in the White House discussed Michael Flynn's suggestion to overturn the election by invoking martial law and rerunning the election in several swing states under military supervision.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] McCarthy and Army Chief of Staff General James McConville later issued a joint statement saying: "There is no role for the U.S. military in determining the outcome of an American election." In a December 20 tweet, Trump dismissed accusations that he wanted to declare martial law as "fake news".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In a December 21 news conference, outgoing attorney general William Barr disavowed several actions reportedly being considered by Trump, including seizing voting machines, appointing a special counsel to investigate voter fraud, and appointing one to investigate Hunter Biden.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Both before and after the election, Trump and other Republican leaders publicly considered asking certain Republican-controlled state legislatures to select presidential electors favoring Trump, even if Biden won the popular vote in those states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In Pennsylvania, a state which Biden won, the president's personal lawyer Rudy Giuliani asked a federal judge to consider allowing the Republican-controlled state legislature to select electors.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In modern times, most states have used a popular vote within their state as the determining factor in who gets all the state's electors, and changing election rules after an election could also violate the Constitution's Due Process Clause.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] As the Trump campaign's lawsuits were repeatedly rejected in court, Trump personally communicated with Republican local and state officials in at least three states, including state legislators, attorneys general, and governors who had supported him during and after the elections.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] He pressured them to overturn the election results in their states by recounting votes, throwing out certain votes, or getting the state legislature to replace the elected Democratic slate of Electoral College members with a Republican slate of electors chosen by the legislature.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In late November, he personally phoned Republican members of two county electoral boards in Michigan, urging them to reverse their vote certifications.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] He invited members of the Michigan state legislature to the White House, where they declined his suggestion that they choose a new slate of electors.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] He repeatedly spoke to the Republican governor of Georgia and the secretary of state, demanding that they reverse their state's election results, and retaliating when they did not, strongly criticizing them in speeches and tweets, and demanding that the governor resign.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On January 4 *The Washington Post* reported that in a phone call on January 2, Trump pressured Georgia secretary of state Brad Raffensperger to overturn the state's result, telling him "I just want to find 11,780 votes" and threatening him with legal action if he did not cooperate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On January 4, 2021, Democratic congressional leaders, believing Trump "engaged in solicitation of, or conspiracy to commit, a number of election crimes," requested the FBI to investigate the incident.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In addition, while some House Republicans tried to defend Trump's Georgia call, Democrats began drafting a censure resolution.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Two months later *The Washington Post* acknowledged that they had misquoted Trump, and added a correction to the article.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Also on January 2, 2021, Trump took part in a mass phone call with nearly 300 state legislators from Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin, in which he urged them to "decertify" the election results in their states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On November 11, Georgia Secretary of State Brad Raffensperger ordered a statewide hand recount of the vote in addition to the normal audit process.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] At the time, Biden held a lead of 13,558 votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The hand recount was concluded on November 19 and affirmed Biden's lead by 12,284 votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Therefore, the hand recount netted Trump 1,274 votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The change in the count was due to a number of human errors, including memory cards that did not upload properly to the state servers, and was not attributable to any fraud in the original tally.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The Trump campaign requested a machine recount, which was estimated to cost taxpayers $200,000 in one Georgia county alone.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On December 7, Biden was confirmed as the winner of the machine recount requested by Trump's campaign.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On November 18, the Trump campaign wired $3 million to pay for partial recounts in Milwaukee County and Dane County, Wisconsin, where Milwaukee and Madison, the two largest cities in the state and Democratic strongholds, are located.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] During the recount, Milwaukee County election commissioner Tim Posnanski said several Republican observers were breaking rules by posing as independents.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The recount started November 20 and concluded on November 29, increasing Biden's lead by 87 votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The presidential electors met in the state capitol of each state and in the District of Columbia on December 14, 2020, and formalized Biden's victory, casting 306 votes for Biden/Harris and 232 votes for Trump/Pence.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Unlike the 2016 election, there were no faithless electors.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In six swing states won by Biden, groups of self-appointed Republican "alternate electors" met on the same day to vote for Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] These alternate slates were not signed by the governors of the states they claim to represent, did not have the backing of any state legislature, and have no legal status.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Even after the casting of the electoral votes and rejection of his lawsuits seeking to overturn the election by at least 86 judges, Trump refused to concede defeat.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In a speech following the Electoral College vote, Biden praised the resiliency of U.S. democratic institutions and the high election turnout (calling it "one of the most amazing demonstrations of civic duty we've ever seen in our country") and called for national unity.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The 117th United States Congress first convened on January 3, 2021, and was scheduled to count and certify the Electoral College votes on January 6, 2021.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] There were 222 Democrats and 212 Republicans in the House; there were 51 Republicans, 46 Democrats, and two independents in the Senate.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Several Republican members of the House and Senate said they would raise objections to the reported count in several states, meeting the requirement that if a member from each body objects, the two houses must meet separately to discuss whether to accept the certified state vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] A statement from the vice president's office said Pence welcomes the plan by Republicans to "raise objections and bring forward evidence" challenging the election results.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On December 28, 2020, Representative Louie Gohmert filed a lawsuit in Texas challenging the constitutionality of the Electoral Count Act of 1887, claiming Vice President Pence has the power and ability to unilaterally decide which slates of electoral votes get counted.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The case was dismissed on January 1, 2021, for lack of both standing and jurisdiction.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The plaintiffs filed an appeal, and the appeal was dismissed by a three-judge panel of the appeals court the next day.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] As vice president, Pence was due to preside over the January 6, 2021, congressional session to count the electoral votes, which is normally a non-controversial, ceremonial event.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In January 2021, Trump began to pressure Pence to take action to overturn the election, demanding both in public and in private that Pence use his position to overturn the election results in swing states and declare Trump and Pence the winners of the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Pence demurred that the law does not give him that power.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Starting in December, Trump called for his supporters to stage a massive protest in Washington, D.C., on January 6 to argue against certification of the electoral vote, using tweets such as "Big protest in D.C. on January 6th.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Be there, will be wild!" D.C. police were concerned, and the National Guard was alerted because several rallies in December had turned violent.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] As part of an organized effort by Republican lawmakers to challenge the results in close states, the House and the Senate were meeting separately to debate the results of Arizona's election and accepting the electoral college ballots submitted.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Several other challenges were also planned.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Congress reconvened that same night, after the Capitol was cleared of trespassers, and leaders of both parties, including Vice President Mike Pence, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Senate Speaker Mitch McConnell urged the legislators to confirm the electors.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The Senate resumed its session at around 8:00 p.m. to finish debating the objection to the Arizona and Pennsylvania electors were also considered.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The joint session completed its work shortly before 4:00 a.m. on Thursday, January 7, declaring Biden and Harris the winners.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The rioters entered the House and Senate chambers and vandalized offices.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Five people died as a result: one person was shot by police, one Capitol Police officer died from a stroke after fisticuffs with rioters, one person died of a heart attack, another of a stroke, and the final death is still under investigation.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Trump was accused of inciting the violence with his rhetoric, an accusation reinforced with an article of impeachment on January 13 for "incitement of insurrection".
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Several commentators viewed the attack on the Capitol Building as an indicator of political instability that could lead to political violence in future elections, ranging from domestic terrorism to a second American Civil War.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Representative Liz Cheney was removed from her party leadership role as Chair of the House Republican Conference, partially for continuing to assert that the election had been fair and that the election results were final.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] Well into Biden's presidency, Trump continued to insist that he had actually won the 2020 election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] As of August 2021, surveys found that a majority of Republicans believe Trump had won the 2020 election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] A widespread rumor predicted that Trump would be somehow reinstated to the presidency in August 2021, although the predicted date of August 13 passed without incident.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On March 31, 2021, the Republican caucus of the Arizona State Senate hired several outside firms to examine the results of the presidential and senatorial elections in Maricopa County, where Biden had won by a large margin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] There had been three previous audits and recounts of that county's results.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The examination was initially funded by $150,000 from the State Senate operating budget; additional funding was to come from outside sources.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] In July the lead firm conducting the review released a summary of major donors, indicating $5.7 million was raised from five groups associated with individuals who had cast doubt on the presidential election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The audit began on April 22, 2021, and was expected to last 60 days.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] The investigation was still ongoing in August when a judge issued an order for the release of documents.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-u-s-presidential-election-p04] On September 24, a preliminary release of the audit claimed to have found minor discrepancies in the original, state-certified count, which had actually widened Biden's margin by 360 votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The **2020 United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio** were held on November 3, 2020, to elect the 16 U.S. representatives from the state of Ohio, one from each of the state's 16 congressional districts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The elections coincided with the 2020 U.S. presidential election, as well as other elections to the House of Representatives, elections to the United States Senate and various state and local elections.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 1st district is based in Cincinnati, stretching southwestward to Ohio's borders with Kentucky and Indiana.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Steve Chabot, who was re-elected with 51.3% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 2nd district takes eastern Cincinnati and its suburbs, including Norwood and Loveland, and stretches eastward along the Ohio River.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Brad Wenstrup, who was re-elected with 57.6% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 3rd district is located entirely within the borders of Franklin County, taking in inner Columbus, Bexley, Whitehall, as well as Franklin County's share of Reynoldsburg.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Democrat Joyce Beatty, who was re-elected with 73.6% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 4th district, nicknamed the "duck district", sprawls from the Columbus exurbs, including Marion and Lima into north-central Ohio, taking in Oberlin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Jim Jordan, who was re-elected with 65.3% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 5th district encompasses Northwestern Ohio, taking in Findlay, Defiance, and Bowling Green.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Bob Latta, who was re-elected with 62.3% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 6th district encompasses Appalachian Ohio, including Steubenville, Marietta, and Ironton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Bill Johnson, who was re-elected with 69.2% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 7th district is based in northeastern Ohio, and includes the city of Canton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Bob Gibbs, who was re-elected with 58.7% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 8th district takes in the northern suburbs of Cincinnati, including Butler County, as well as taking in Springfield.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Warren Davidson, who was re-elected with 66.6% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 9th district spans the coast of Lake Erie from Toledo to the west side of Cleveland, taking in Port Clinton, Sandusky, Lorain, Lakewood, Brook Park, and Brooklyn.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Democrat Marcy Kaptur, who was re-elected with 67.8% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 10th district encompasses the Dayton metro area, including Dayton and the surrounding suburbs.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Mike Turner, who was re-elected with 55.9% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 11th district takes in eastern Cleveland and its suburbs, including Euclid, Cleveland Heights, and Warrensville Heights, as well as stretching southward into Richfield and parts of Akron.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Democrat Marcia Fudge, who was re-elected with 82.2% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 12th district encompasses the northern Columbus metro area, taking in the northern Columbus suburbs, including Dublin, Westerville, Gahanna, and New Albany, as well as Newark, Mansfield, and Zanesville.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Troy Balderson, who was re-elected with 51.4% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 13th district covers the Mahoning Valley in northeastern Ohio, including Youngstown and eastern parts of Akron.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Democrat Tim Ryan, who was re-elected with 61.0% of the vote in 2018, and ran for president in 2020, though he dropped out on October 24, 2019.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 14th district is located in Northeast Ohio, taking in the eastern suburbs and exurbs of Cleveland, including Mayfield Heights, Solon, and Independence, as well as Ashtabula, Lake, and Geauga counties, northern Portage County, and northeastern Summit County.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican David Joyce, who was re-elected with 55.2% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 15th district encompasses the southern Columbus metro area, taking in the western and eastern suburbs of Columbus, including Upper Arlington, Hilliard, and Grove City, as well as Athens.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Steve Stivers, who was re-elected with 58.3% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The 16th district takes in the western suburbs of Cleveland, including Westlake, Parma, and Strongsville, as well as Medina, Norton, and North Canton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-ohio] The incumbent was Republican Anthony Gonzalez, who was first elected with 56.7% of the vote in 2018.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] The **2020 United States presidential election in Pennsylvania** was held on Tuesday, November 3, 2020, as part of the 2020 United States presidential election in which all 50 states plus the District of Columbia participated.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Pennsylvania had 20 electoral votes in the Electoral College.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Although Trump had won the state in 2016 by a narrow margin of 0.72%, Biden was able to reclaim the state, winning it by a similarly narrow 1.16% margin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Because of the way the state counted in-person ballots first, Trump started with a wide lead on election night.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] However, over the next few days, Biden greatly closed the margin due to outstanding votes from Democratic-leaning areas, most notably Philadelphia and Pittsburgh, as well as mail-in ballots from all parts of the state which strongly favored him.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] On the morning of November 6, election-calling organization Decision Desk HQ forecast that Biden had won Pennsylvania's 20 electoral votes, and with them the election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] The following morning, November 7, at the same time that the Trump campaign was holding a press conference outside of a Philadelphia landscaping business, nearly all major news organizations followed suit and called Pennsylvania for Biden, proclaiming him president-elect.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] At the same time, he reclaimed two of the three large industrial counties which had voted Democratic for at least six consecutive elections before Trump flipped them in 2016: Erie and Northampton.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] While Trump prevailed in the third, Luzerne County, he did so by a reduced margin with respect to 2016; and Biden increased the margin of victory in his birth county, Lackawanna County, which Trump had nearly flipped in 2016.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Biden halted the four-election Democratic slide in formerly traditionally Democratic Westmoreland County, where, before 2020, Al Gore had been the last Democrat to improve on the previous nominee's vote share (and which had given Trump his margin in the state in 2016).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Biden became the first Democratic candidate running for president to garner at least 100,000 votes in the Republican stronghold county of Lancaster.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] He also became the second presidential candidate since 1964, the last time the county voted for a Democrat, to get at least 40% of the vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] This was due to the large number of votes Biden received from the city of Lancaster and a competitive margin in voting precincts in and around Lititz and Columbia.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Despite Biden's victory, Pennsylvania weighed in for this election as 3.3% more Republican than the national average.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] This is the second consecutive presidential election in which Pennsylvania voted to the right of the nation.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Previously, it had not done so since 1948.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] With Ohio, Florida, and Iowa backing the losing candidate for the first time since 1960, 1992, and 2000 respectively, this election established Pennsylvania, Wisconsin, and Michigan as the states with the longest bellwether streak still in effect today.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] The last time any of them voted against the winning candidate was 2004, when all three voted for the losing Democrat John Kerry.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Biden became the first Democrat to win the White House without carrying Luzerne County since Harry Truman in 1948.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] This was the first election since 1932 that the county voted for the statewide loser.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] The primary elections were originally scheduled for April 28, 2020, also originally joining several northeastern states in holding primaries on the same date, including Connecticut, Delaware, Maryland, New York, and Rhode Island.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] On March 26, Pennsylvania joined several other states in moving its primary to June 2 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Even though the Republican National Committee mailed Pennsylvania voters encouraging mail-in voting, describing it as a "convenient and secure" option, most Republicans expressed opposition to the prospect.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Earlier, the Republican-controlled House blocked a proposal to mail every Pennsylvanian a mail-in ballot application.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] This was in response to President Trump's skepticism of the practice, expressing concern mail-in voting may result in voter fraud that would potentially benefit the Democratic Party.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Trump was declared the winner in the Republican primary, and received all of the state's 34 pledged delegates to the 2020 Republican National Convention (the state also has 54 unpledged delegates).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] The Green Caucus was held during April 2020 and was won by Howie Hawkins.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] 9,098,998 residents registered to vote by the voter registration deadline on October 15, which had been extended from its original date on October 13 by court order.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p01] Biden and Trump both won half of the 18 congressional districts in Pennsylvania, including each winning one held by the opposite party.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Throughout the year, Pennsylvania was regarded as the most important (or likely tipping-point) state in the entire election; Pennsylvania had 20 electoral votes, and it was one of the closest states of the 2016 presidential election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Both candidates aggressively played for the state; Trump needed the state as it represented his narrow path to re-election, while Biden needed the state to rebuild the blue wall, which Trump had broken in 2016 by carrying the northern industrial states of Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Historically, Pennsylvania has usually been a competitive state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] During the Second Party System from 1828 to 1852, it voted for the winner of every election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] From the Civil War on, it has generally had a partisan lean; during the Third and Fourth Party Systems, Pennsylvania was a classic Yankee Republican state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] When Franklin Roosevelt carried it in 1936, he became the first Democrat in eighty years to do so.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Between 1936 and 1988, neither major party carried Pennsylvania for more than three straight presidential elections, although between 1952 and 1988, it voted Democratic in every close election (1960, 1968, 1976), and consistently voted more Democratic than the nation.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Starting in 1992, Pennsylvania became part of the blue wall—the group of states that voted Democratic for six straight elections from 1992 through 2012.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] In 2016, it was one of three blue wall states that Trump won on his way to an upset victory.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] State Republicans sought to require that only mail-in ballots received by Election Day be counted.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] The Commonwealth's Supreme Court rejected their demands, deciding that, due to probable delays due to the ongoing coronavirus and U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Postal Service crisis, ballots received up to three days after Election Day would also be counted.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Republicans then appealed the decision to the U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Supreme Court justices produced a 4–4 tie (as the late Ruth Bader Ginsburg's seat remained vacant when the ruling was issued), with Chief Justice John Roberts siding with the three liberal justices, allowing the state supreme court decision to stand.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] At 1.17%, Biden's winning margin percentage in Pennsylvania was the smallest ever for a Democratic presidential candidate who won Pennsylvania.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Pennsylvania remained redder than the country in 2020 even as Biden won it, by about 3.3%.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] As in Michigan and Wisconsin, Biden ran behind Barack Obama's performances in 2008 and 2012, though he received more votes total in the state this cycle due to record-breaking turnout.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Biden's margin of victory was also less than Al Gore's 4.2% margin of victory in 2000 and John Kerry's 2.5% margin of victory in 2004.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] As for Trump, he easily set the record for total number of votes for a Republican candidate in Pennsylvania history (as with Biden, largely due to record-breaking turnout).
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] With 48.84% of the vote, he did slightly outpace both his own vote share in 2016 (48.18%) and George W.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Bush's in 2004 (48.42%), the latter of which had previously stood as the highest Republican vote share in the state since 1988.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Biden's strongest base of support was the Philadelphia metro area.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] In the city of Philadelphia itself, Biden won by 63.4%, a weaker win than Hillary Clinton's 66.9% margin in the city in 2016, but still better than Kerry's 61.1% margin in 2004 or Gore's 62.0% margin in 2000.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Donald Trump improved his vote share in Philadelphia by 2.5%, and, as of the counting on November 8, held a majority of the vote in the 26th, 58th, and 66th wards.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Pennsylvania's 2nd congressional district, encompassing Northeast Philadelphia, swung towards Trump from 2016 to 2020.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] However, Biden improved on Hillary Clinton dramatically in the Main Line counties of Montgomery and Chester, as well as, to a lesser extent, Delaware, increasing the Democratic vote share in these counties by 4.2%, 5.9%, and 3.5%, respectively, and winning them all by double digits.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Before 1992, all three had been Republican strongholds in the state, and Chester had been considered a swing county as recently as 2012, when Romney narrowly carried it, but all three have drifted towards the Democratic column, as they tend to be socially liberal.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Biden also performed strongly in Pennsylvania's other urban, suburban, and exurban areas.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Crucially, he carried Allegheny County (Pittsburgh) by 20.4%, the widest margin any nominee had won the county by since 1992.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Centre and Dauphin both remained in the Democratic column; in the past, these counties voted Republican, though Centre County is home to Pennsylvania State University, while Dauphin County, home of Harrisburg, has followed the trend of urban areas becoming more Democratic.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] In suburban Cumberland County, adjacent to Harrisburg, Biden shaved Trump's margin from 17.8% to 10.5%.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Northampton and Erie were the only counties to flip from one party to the other; Northampton has voted for the winner of the state in every election from 1952 on.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Trump maintained much of his momentum throughout rural and industrial Pennsylvania from four years earlier, with convincing victories in counties that were once competitive or even Democratic-leaning.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] He kept Luzerne County (Wilkes-Barre), which had voted Democratic six elections in a row before 2016 (and which had voted with the winner of the state from 1936 through 2016), in his column, although his margin in it was cut from 19.3% to 14.3%.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Trump also won the former Democratic stronghold of Westmoreland County, although his margin in this county, crucial to his win in 2016, declined.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Other previously competitive counties that Trump performed well in included Berks and Cambria, both of which voted for Obama in 2008.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Trump further ran up the score in other conservative exurban counties, most notably in Lancaster and Lebanon counties, though his margin shrank somewhat in both.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Trump won whites in the state by 15 points, although like in the rest of the country, there was a clear disparity between college-educated and non-college-educated whites.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Biden won whites with a college degree by 9 points, while Trump excelled with whites without a college degree, winning this group by 32 points.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Additionally, there was a gender disparity with the white vote; Trump won white men by 15 points, but only carried white women by 3 points.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Finally, there was an age gap; Biden won young voters by double-digit margins, whereas Trump performed strongly with middle-aged voters; senior citizens were more even, breaking slightly for Trump.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Within minority blocs, Biden fared well, as he won black voters by 87 points, and won Latinos by 42 points.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Three other critical voting blocs broke for Biden this cycle; he won independent voters by 8 points, moderates by 17 points, and first-time voters by 23 points.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] On November 25, 2020, the Pennsylvania Senate Majority (Republican) Policy committee held a public hearing regarding the counting of ballots in this election.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Trump planned to attend the meeting but he canceled the trip.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Also, on November 25, after a group of Republican congressmen had filed a lawsuit to stop certification on Sunday November 22, Judge Patricia McCullough (R) ruled to halt further state certifications pending a hearing.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] The Pennsylvania Supreme Court then ruled Saturday night on November 28 to unanimously overturn Judge Patricia McCullough's ruling to halt certification because no fraud was alleged and both parties could have objected throughout the year, but did not.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] As required by state law, all counties completed a post-election sample audit.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] With the exception of three counties, Pennsylvania's counties also participated in a voluntary risk-limiting audit pilot.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Both types of audits confirmed the certified results.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Lycoming County completed a hand recount and did not find any major discrepancy.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Butler County also completed a hand recount in two precincts and found no inaccuracies.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] On January 6, 2021, as Congress certified the Electoral College results confirming President-elect Joe Biden and Vice President-elect Kamala Harris as the winners, there was an objection to Pennsylvania's 20 electoral votes, brought forward by U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] Representative Scott Perry of Pennsylvania's 10th congressional district and officially signed onto by U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/2020-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania-p02] The objection failed 7–92 in the Senate, and 138–282 in the House.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The **American Solidarity Party** (**ASP**), formerly the **Christian Democratic Party USA** (**CDPUSA**), is an American syncretic political party founded in 2011 by David "Frost" Harris, Kirk Morrison, and Jack Quirk.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] It is a Christian democratic political party with center-left economic values and center-right social values.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The party has a Solidarity National Committee (SNC) and has numerous active state and local chapters.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The American Solidarity Party has been characterized as socially conservative and economically progressive.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The ASP encourages social development along the lines of subsidiarity and sphere sovereignty, with a stated emphasis on "the importance of strong nuclear families, local communities, and voluntary associations".
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The party adheres to a consistent life ethic, opposing reproductive rights such as abortion in all cases where the mother's life is not in danger, IVF, and surrogacy, as well as assisted suicide, capital punishment, euthanasia, and unjust war.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] They broadly support universal healthcare, immigration, and welfare.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] It favors fiscally progressive policies, as well as a social market economy with a distributist character, which seeks "widespread economic participation and ownership", and providing a social safety net program.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] In the 2024 United States presidential election, it was on the ballot in Alabama, Alaska, Arkansas, Florida, Hawaii, Louisiana, Mississippi, and Ohio, with Peter Sonski as the party's nominee.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The American Solidarity party was founded in 2011 as the Christian Democratic Party USA (CDPUSA) by founders David "Frost" Harris, Kirk Morrison, and Jack Quirk.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The party's original name was inspired by its European counterparts, the Polish trade union known as *Solidarity*, and the current one reflects its more developed ideology and focus in the years since.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The ASP mascot is the pelican, a traditional symbol of charity.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] In 2012, the CDPUSA endorsed the independent candidacy of Joe Schriner for president.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] In December 2020, the American Solidarity Party joined the board of the Coalition for Free and Open Elections (COFOE).
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The American Solidarity Party largely adheres to the ideology of Christian democracy, which has been influenced by Catholic social teaching, Neo-Calvinist theology and the social teachings espoused by other traditions of Christianity in various parts of the world.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] As such, the ASP looks to the Christian democratic movements in Europe and the Americas.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The American Solidarity Party has been characterized as conservative on social issues while supporting government intervention in economic matters, making it communitarian.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The American Solidarity Party opposes abortion, euthanasia, and capital punishment on the basis of the sanctity of human life.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] It views the traditional family as being central to society.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The American Solidarity Party advocates for a sympathetic approach to immigration.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] They believe in balancing the need for secure borders with a commitment to human dignity.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] This involves addressing the root causes of migration, such as the impact of the country's military, political, and economic power abroad.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The American Solidarity Party supports a universal healthcare system as well as an economy containing widespread distribution of productive property, in particular increased worker ownership and management of their production.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The American Solidarity Party is non-interventionist in its foreign policy, using peace as its guiding principle.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] It supports foreign aid and nonviolent diplomacy, while opposing violent military action as a means to resolve conflicts.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The American Solidarity Party advocates for electoral reform, aiming to combat what they call a "political oligarchy" and gridlock.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] They propose proportional representation for the House of Representatives, endorse ranked-choice voting or approval voting in all elections, and support easy voter registration.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The party also emphasizes fair access for independent candidates, access to impartial information, and pilot programs for electronic voting with consideration for security concerns.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Daniel Silliman writes that the American Solidarity Party, as with other Christian-democratic political parties, draws from Catholic social teaching and Neo-Calvinist theology.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Its strongest support is in California and Texas, according to the *Madera Tribune* (of Madera, California).
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Members of the American Solidarity Party use the demonym "Solidarist" to refer to themselves.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The ASP has run candidates for federal, state, and local offices.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] There are currently three ASP members serving in elected office.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] During the 2016 presidential election season, the American Solidarity Party held an online convention on July 9, 2016, which nominated Amir Azarvan of Georgia for president and Mike Maturen of Michigan for vice-president.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] However, Azarvan subsequently withdrew, and in response the ticket was revised, with Maturen running for president and Juan Muñoz of Texas running for vice-president.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] For the 2016 election, the American Solidarity Party was listed on the ballot in Colorado.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] It was a certified write-in option in Alabama, California, Georgia, Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota, New Hampshire, New Jersey, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Texas, Vermont, and Washington.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Maturen received 6,697 votes in Colorado.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] In the 2020 U.S. presidential election, Brian Carroll, Joe Schriner, and Joshua Perkins announced their candidacies for the ASP nomination.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Carroll was declared the winner of the nomination on September 9, 2019.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] For the 2020 election, the American Solidarity Party was on the ballot in Arkansas, Colorado, Guam, Illinois, Louisiana, Mississippi, Rhode Island, Vermont and Wisconsin.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] On June 2, 2023, Peter Sonski won the nomination of the party for President of the United States.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The primary was conducted by an online members' vote.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The vice presidential nominee, Lauren Onak, was selected by Sonski before the national convention in early July in Plano, Texas, and she was formally nominated there.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The party was on the ballot in Arkansas, Alaska, Hawaii, Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, and Ohio.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Sonski had write-in access in 33 additional states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Carroll had write-in access in 31 additional states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Maturen had write-in access in 18 additional states.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] In addition to the candidates below, Mike Vick ran as a write-in candidate for Illinois's 2nd congressional district in 2024.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Illinois does not report write-in votes separately.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] The party also endorsed Democrat and AND Campaign co-founder Pastor Chris Butler for U.S.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Congress in Illinois's 1st congressional district in 2022.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] He was eliminated in the Democratic primary, receiving 3,707 votes.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] In addition to the candidates below, Solidarity National Committee member Dr.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Tyler Martin ran for governor of Nebraska in 2022.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Nebraska does not report write-in votes separately, meaning Martin's vote share is unknown.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] In addition to the candidates below, in 2024, Amar Patel ran for state representative in Illinois' 48th district, and Jonathan Bruce ran for state representative in South Carolina's 8th district.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Neither state reports write-in votes separately.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] May have received write-in votes, which have not yet been reported by the state.
[src:american-solidarity-party/american-solidarity-party] Compiled from results reported by local governments.
